 in certified units. (That is 0.6% for each additional year after 1990)\n*between 2000\u2013present are required to have their available claimed figures supported by 70\u201380% in certified units. (That is 0.66% for each additional year after 2000)\n}}\n{{efn|name=songs|Below you can get an understanding as to when certifications for songs are added to the total certified sales of the listed artists.\n* One lead artist and one featured artist. (The issued certification(s) should be added to the total of both, the lead artist and the featured artist as both will have almost equal amount of part).\n* Two lead artists.(The issued certification(s) should be added to the total of both lead artists as both will have almost equal amount of part).\n* Two lead artists and one featured artist. (The issued certification(s) should be added to the total of both lead artists as well as the featured artist. Both lead artists will play a significant part in a song and the part of the featured artist also should be significant enough). \n* One lead artist and two featured artists. (The issued certification(s) should be added to the total of the lead artist and to the total of both featured artists as almost all should have equal amount of part).\n}}\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Music industry}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:List Of best-selling music artists}}\n[[Category:Lists of bestsellers|Musicians]]\n[[Category:Lists of musicians|Best-selling]]\n[[Category:Rock music]]\n[[Category:Popular music]]\n[[Category:Lists of best-selling music artists]]\n", "name_user": "Politsi", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e250 million or more records", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_best-selling_music_artists"}
{"title_page": "Lower Tamar Lake", "text_new": "[[File:Lower Tamar Lake spillway - geograph.org.uk - 914820.jpg|thumb|right|The spillway (in 1985).]]\n'''Lower Tamar Lake''' is located on the [[Devon]]-[[Cornwall]] border, in [[England]], near [[Alfardisworthy]].<ref name=os>[[Ordnance Survey]] mapping</ref>\n\nIt was constructed in the 1820s to supply water to the [[Bude Canal]]. It is now a nature reserve.\n\nThe reservoir has been formed by damming the [[River Tamar]]. To the north (upstream) is the newer [[Upper Tamar Lake]],<ref name=os/> a reservoir used for public water supply.\n\nThe county boundary originally ran along the (natural) route of the River Tamar, but was re-aligned along a (now disused) re-routing of the river to the reservoir's west side, placing the lake in Devon.<ref name=os/>\n\n==References==\n{{Portal|Cornwall|Devon}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.bude-canal.co.uk/map8.htm Bude Canal and Harbour Society] 1904 map ''showing the reservoir, the then route of the Tamar and the feeder to the Bude Canal''\n\n{{coord|50.873|-4.425|type:waterbody_region:GB|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Environment of Cornwall]] \n[[Category:Environment of Devon]]\n[[Category:Reservoirs in Devon]]\n[[Category:Reservoirs in Cornwall]]\n[[Category:River Tamar]]\n\n{{Cornwall-geo-stub}}\n{{Devon-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "[[File:Lower Tamar Lake spillway - geograph.org.uk - 914820.jpg|thumb|right|The spillway (in 1985).]]\n'''Lower Tamar Lake''' is located on the [[Devon]]-[[Cornwall]] border, in [[England]], near [[Alfardisworthy]].<ref name=os>[[Ordnance Survey]] mapping</ref>\n\nIt was constructed in the 1820s to supply water to the [[Bude Canal]]. It is now a nature reserve.\n\nThe reservoir has been formed by damming the [[River Tamar]]. To the north (upstream) is the newer [[Upper Tamar Lake]],<ref name=os/> a reservoir used for public water supply.\n\nThe county boundary originally ran along the (natural) route of the River Tamar, but was re-aligned along a (now disused) re-routing of the river to the reservoir's west side, placing the lake in Devon.<ref name=os/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.bude-canal.co.uk/map8.htm Bude Canal and Harbour Society] 1904 map ''showing the reservoir, the then route of the Tamar and the feeder to the Bude Canal''\n\n{{coord|50.873|-4.425|type:waterbody_region:GB|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Environment of Cornwall]] \n[[Category:Environment of Devon]]\n[[Category:Reservoirs in Devon]]\n[[Category:Reservoirs in Cornwall]]\n[[Category:River Tamar]]\n\n{{Cornwall-geo-stub}}\n{{Devon-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Gazamp", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:AddedPortal:Cornwall", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lower_Tamar_Lake"}
{"title_page": "Hunderman", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Hunderman\n| other_name                      = Hundurman Broq\n| official_name                   = \n| nickname                        = \n| settlement_type                 = Village\n| image_skyline                   =\n| alt                             = \n| image_caption                   = View of Hunderman Village\n| pushpin_map                     = India Ladakh#India\n| pushpin_map_alt                 = \n| coordinates                     = {{coord|34.616|N|76.130|E|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type                = Country\n| subdivision_name                = {{flag|India}}\n| subdivision_type1               = [[States and union territories of India|Union Territory]]\n| subdivision_name1               = [[Ladakh]]\n| subdivision_type2               = [[List of districts of India|District]]\n| subdivision_name2               = [[Kargil district|Kargil]]\n| subdivision_type3               = [[List of tehsils in India|Tehsil]]\n| subdivision_name3               = [[Kargil]]\n| established_title               = <!-- Established -->\n| established_date                = \n| founder                         = \n| named_for                       = \n| government_type                 = [[Panchayati raj (India)|Panchayati raj]]\n| governing_body                  = [[Gram panchayat]]\n| unit_pref                       = Metric\n| area_footnotes                  = \n| area_rank                       = \n| area_total_km2                  = \n| elevation_footnotes             = \n| elevation_m                     = \n| population_as_of                = 2011\n| population_total                = 216\n| population_footnotes            = \n| demographics_type1              = Languages\n| demographics1_title1            = Official\n| demographics1_info1             = [[Balti language|Balti]], [[Ladakhi language|Ladakhi]], [[Urdu]]\n| timezone1                       = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1                     = +5:30\n| postal_code_type                = <-- [[Postal Index Number|PIN]] -->\n| postal_code                     = \n| registration_plate              = \n| website                         = \n| footnotes                       = \n| blank_name_sec1                 = <-- [[Census of India|Census]] code -->\n| blank_info_sec1                 = \n}}\n\n'''Hunderman''' or '''Hundarmaan''' is one of the northernmost villages in [[India]] and is situated in the [[Kargil district]] of [[Ladakh]]. It is located 10&nbsp;km from [[Kargil]], the district headquarters, and is on the banks of the [[Dras River|Drass River]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/Hundurmaan/@34.6167573,76.1301833,16z/data=!4m13!1m7!3m6!1s0x38e33d1f91087b7b:0x6f46ffd6b63f674d!2sHundurmaan!3b1!8m2!3d34.6167573!4d76.1301833!3m4!1s0x38e33d1f91087b7b:0x6f46ffd6b63f674d!8m2!3d34.6167573!4d76.1301833|title=Hunderman Village, Kargil (Google Maps)|work=Google Maps|accessdate=5 February 2020}}</ref> It was under Pakistan's control until [[Indo-Pakistani War of 1971|1971]]. Geographically, Hunderman lies in the Baltistan Region. There are two parts of Hunderman: Lower Hunderman and Upper Hunderman.\n\n== History ==\n=== Indo-Pakistan conflicts ===\nAt the end of the [[Indo-Pakistani War of 1947]], Hunderman came under the control of [[Pakistan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/Leisure/nkoE1dc52oYwoWRNmhEeYK/A-portrait-of-a-village-on-the-border.html|title=A portrait of a village on the border|work=Livemint|accessdate=5 February 2020}}</ref> The Indian Army recaptured Hunderman after the [[Indo-Pakistani War of 1971]].\n\n===Attractions===\n\n1. Unlock Hunderman\u2013Museum of Memories<ref>https://www.cntraveller.in/story/loc-village-poa/</ref>\n\n== Demographics ==\n\nAccording to the [[2011 census of India]], Hunderman has a population of about 216.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ Demographics (2011 Census)\n! !! Total !! Male !! Female\n|-\n| Population || 216 || 107 || 109\n|-\n| Children aged below 6 years || 27 || 14 || 13\n|-\n| [[Scheduled caste]] || 0 || 0 || 0\n|-\n| [[Scheduled tribe]] || 215 || \u2013 || \u2013\n|-\n| Literates || 118 || 70 || 48\n|-\n| Literacy Rate || 54.6% || \u2013 || 22.2%\n|-\n| Workers (all) || 38 || \u2013 || \u2013\n|-\n| Non-workers || 178 || \u2013 || \u2013\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* [https://www.livemint.com/Leisure/nkoE1dc52oYwoWRNmhEeYK/A-portrait-of-a-village-on-the-border.html Hunderman, the portrait village on the India-Pak border], Livemint, 11 August 2017.\n\n{{Ladakh}}\n{{Kargil district}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Kargil tehsil]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Hunderman\n| other_name                      = Hundurman Broq\n| official_name                   = \n| nickname                        = \n| settlement_type                 = Village\n| image_skyline                   =\n| alt                             = \n| image_caption                   = View of Hunderman Village\n| pushpin_map                     = India Ladakh#India\n| pushpin_map_alt                 = \n| coordinates                     = {{coord|34.616|N|76.130|E|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type                = Country\n| subdivision_name                = {{flag|India}}\n| subdivision_type1               = [[States and union territories of India|Union Territory]]\n| subdivision_name1               = [[Ladakh]]\n| subdivision_type2               = [[List of districts of India|District]]\n| subdivision_name2               = [[Kargil district|Kargil]]\n| subdivision_type3               = <-- [[Tehsil]] -->\n| subdivision_name3               = \n| established_title               = <!-- Established -->\n| established_date                = \n| founder                         = \n| named_for                       = \n| government_type                 = [[Panchayati raj (India)|Panchayati raj]]\n| governing_body                  = [[Gram panchayat]]\n| unit_pref                       = Metric\n| area_footnotes                  = \n| area_rank                       = \n| area_total_km2                  = \n| elevation_footnotes             = \n| elevation_m                     = \n| population_as_of                = 2011\n| population_total                = 216\n| population_footnotes            = \n| demographics_type1              = Languages\n| demographics1_title1            = Official\n| demographics1_info1             = [[Balti language|Balti]], [[Ladakhi language|Ladakhi]], [[Urdu]]\n| timezone1                       = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1                     = +5:30\n| postal_code_type                = <-- [[Postal Index Number|PIN]] -->\n| postal_code                     = \n| registration_plate              = \n| website                         = \n| footnotes                       = \n| blank_name_sec1                 = <-- [[Census of India|Census]] code -->\n| blank_info_sec1                 = \n}}\n\n'''Hunderman''' or '''Hundarmaan''' is one of the northernmost villages in [[India]] and is situated in the [[Kargil district]] of [[Ladakh]]. It is located 10&nbsp;km from [[Kargil]], the district headquarters, and is on the banks of the [[Dras River|Drass River]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/Hundurmaan/@34.6167573,76.1301833,16z/data=!4m13!1m7!3m6!1s0x38e33d1f91087b7b:0x6f46ffd6b63f674d!2sHundurmaan!3b1!8m2!3d34.6167573!4d76.1301833!3m4!1s0x38e33d1f91087b7b:0x6f46ffd6b63f674d!8m2!3d34.6167573!4d76.1301833|title=Hunderman Village, Kargil (Google Maps)|work=Google Maps|accessdate=5 February 2020}}</ref> It was under Pakistan's control until [[Indo-Pakistani War of 1971|1971]]. Geographically, Hunderman lies in the Baltistan Region. There are two parts of Hunderman: Lower Hunderman and Upper Hunderman.\n\n== History ==\n=== Indo-Pakistan conflicts ===\nAt the end of the [[Indo-Pakistani War of 1947]], Hunderman came under the control of [[Pakistan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/Leisure/nkoE1dc52oYwoWRNmhEeYK/A-portrait-of-a-village-on-the-border.html|title=A portrait of a village on the border|work=Livemint|accessdate=5 February 2020}}</ref> The Indian Army recaptured Hunderman after the [[Indo-Pakistani War of 1971]].\n\n===Attractions===\n\n1. Unlock Hunderman\u2013Museum of Memories<ref>https://www.cntraveller.in/story/loc-village-poa/</ref>\n\n== Demographics ==\n\nAccording to the [[2011 census of India]], Hunderman has a population of about 216.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ Demographics (2011 Census)\n! !! Total !! Male !! Female\n|-\n| Population || 216 || 107 || 109\n|-\n| Children aged below 6 years || 27 || 14 || 13\n|-\n| [[Scheduled caste]] || 0 || 0 || 0\n|-\n| [[Scheduled tribe]] || 215 || \u2013 || \u2013\n|-\n| Literates || 118 || 70 || 48\n|-\n| Literacy Rate || 54.6% || \u2013 || 22.2%\n|-\n| Workers (all) || 38 || \u2013 || \u2013\n|-\n| Non-workers || 178 || \u2013 || \u2013\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* [https://www.livemint.com/Leisure/nkoE1dc52oYwoWRNmhEeYK/A-portrait-of-a-village-on-the-border.html Hunderman, the portrait village on the India-Pak border], Livemint, 11 August 2017.\n\n{{Ladakh}}\n{{Kargil district}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Kargil tehsil]]\n", "name_user": "FlyJet777", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hunderman"}
{"title_page": "Catholic Church sexual abuse cases in Australia", "text_new": "{{see also|Catholic Church sexual abuse cases}}\n{{short description|Catholic Church sexual abuse cases in Australia}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=November 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n'''Catholic sexual abuse cases in Australia''', like [[Catholic sexual abuse scandal]]s elsewhere, have involved convictions, trials and ongoing investigations into allegations of [[sex crimes]] committed by [[Catholic priest]]s,  members of [[Abuse by members of Roman Catholic orders|religious orders]] and other personnel which have come to light in recent decades, along with the growing awareness of sexual abuse within other religious and secular institutions.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/vaticancityandholysee/7429933/Child-abuse-scandals-faced-by-Roman-Catholic-Church.html |title=Child abuse scandals faced by Roman Catholic Church |date=12 March 2010 |work=The Telegraph |location=United Kingdom |accessdate=21 September 2011}}</ref> Criticisms of the Church have centred both on the nature and extent of abuse, and on historical and contemporary management of allegations by Church officials. Internally, the Church began updating its protocols in the 1990s, and papal apologies for abuse in Australia were made by [[Pope John Paul II]] and [[Pope Benedict XVI]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vatican.va/holy_father/john_paul_ii/apost_exhortations/documents/hf_jp-ii_exh_20011122_ecclesia-in-oceania_en.html |author=Pope John Paul II |work=Apostolic exhortation |publisher=Libreria Editrice Vaticana |title=Ecclesia in Oceania |location=Rome |date=22 November 2001 |accessdate=30 March 2012 }}</ref> A number of government enquiries have also examined church practices - most notably the 2015-17 [[Royal Commission into Institutional Responses to Child Sexual Abuse]]. The Royal Commission established that some 4,444 claimants alleged incidents of child sexual abuse in 4,756 reported claims to Catholic Church authorities (some claimants made a claim of child sexual abuse against more than one Catholic Church authority) and at least 1,880 suspected abusers from 1980 to 2015. Most of those suspected of abuse were Catholic priests and religious brothers and 62 percent of the survivors who told the commission they were abused in religious institutions were abused in a Catholic facility.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/12/14/world/australia/australia-sexual-abuse-children.html|title=Australia and Catholic Church \u2018Failed\u2019 Abused Children, Inquiry Finds|author=Williams, Jecqueline|date=14 December 2017|newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref><ref name=\"childabuseroyalcommission.gov.au\">[http://childabuseroyalcommission.gov.au/getattachment/e352891e-2cb8-4abf-96b9-4449296c470b/Analysis-of-claims-of-child-sexual-abuse-made-with Royal Commission: ANALYSIS OF CLAIMS OF CHILD SEXUAL ABUSE MADE WITH RESPECT TO CATHOLIC CHURCH INSTITUTIONS IN AUSTRALIA] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170731111106/http://childabuseroyalcommission.gov.au/getattachment/e352891e-2cb8-4abf-96b9-4449296c470b/Analysis-of-claims-of-child-sexual-abuse-made-with |date=31 July 2017 }}; June 2017</ref>\n\nAustralia's Catholic leaders had been among the first in the world to publicly address management of child abuse: In 1996, the church issued a document, ''Towards Healing'', which it described as seeking to \"establish a compassionate and just system for dealing with complaints of abuse\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.adelaide.catholic.org.au/sites/ProfessionalStandards/dealing-with-complaints-of-abuse/towards-healing |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722062507/http://www.adelaide.catholic.org.au/sites/ProfessionalStandards/dealing-with-complaints-of-abuse/towards-healing |archivedate=22 July 2011 |title=Towards Healing |work=Professional Standards Office |publisher=Australian Catholic Bishops Conference |year=1996 |accessdate=30 March 2012 }}</ref> Inquiries have since established that historically, Church officials had often failed to prevent future abuse by clergy who had come to their attention by [[Parish transfers of abusive priests|transferring clergy]] and religious to new parishes or dioceses, and not stripping them of their religious status.<ref>{{cite news |first=James |last=Campbell |title=Church must face scrutiny for child sex abuse |work=Sunday Herald Sun |date=29 August 2010 |url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/opinion/church-must-face-scrutiny-for-child-sex-abuse/story-fn5sqiu3-1225911324431 |accessdate=24 September 2011 |location=Australia }}</ref> A widely reported 2012 claim in a Victorian police report that 43 suicide deaths were directly related to abuse by clergy spurred the formation of a Victorian state Parliamentary  inquiry into the Handling of Child Abuse by Religious and other Organisations.<ref>[http://www.theaustralian.com.au/national-affairs/in-depth/royal-commission/victoria-police-in-false-claim-on-childabuse-suicides/news-story/ac8da079994e08ab94eec0c951f0b1e9 Victoria Police in false claim on child-abuse suicides]; theaustralian.com.au; 25 July</ref><ref>{{cite news |author1=McKenzie, Nick |author2=Baker, Richard |author3=Lee, Jane |title=Church's suicide victims |work=Canberra Times |date=13 April 2012 |url=http://www.canberratimes.com.au/victoria/churchs-suicide-victims-20120412-1wwox.html |accessdate=2 July 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120613181306/http://www.canberratimes.com.au/victoria/churchs-suicide-victims-20120412-1wwox.html |archive-date=13 June 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In October 2012, the Chief Commissioner of Victoria Police, [[Ken Lay (police officer)|Ken Lay]], in a submission to a parliamentary inquiry on the issue, recommended that some of the church's actions to hinder investigations (including dissuading victims from reporting to police, failing to engage with police and alerting suspects of allegations against them) be criminalised.<ref>{{cite news |author1=Lee, Jane |author2=Zwartz, Barney |title=Police slam Catholic Church |work=The Age |location=Australia |date=11 October 2012 |accessdate= |url=http://www.theage.com.au/victoria/police-slam-catholic-church-20121010-27dr2.html }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Gillard Government]] called a wide-ranging Royal Commission in 2013 to examine religious and non-religious institutions and their responses to child abuse allegations. [[Denis Hart|Archbishop Hart]], president of the [[Australian Catholic Bishops Conference]], said he welcomed the [[Royal Commission]], as did the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Sydney|Archbishop of Sydney]], Cardinal [[George Pell]] who said he hoped it would help victims and stop a \"smear campaign\" against the Church.<ref>{{cite news |title=Abuse inquiry to run 'as long as it takes' |work=The Australian |date=13 November 2012 |url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/breaking-news/catholic-archbishop-welcomes-inquiry/story-fn3dxiwe-1226515563793 |accessdate=13 November 2012 |author=Drape, Julian |agency=AAP }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title = Cardinal Welcomes Royal Commission | work = Catholic Communications, Sydney Archdiocese | date = 16 November 2012 | url = http://www.sydneycatholic.org/news/latest_news/2012/20121115_453.shtml | accessdate = 20 November 2012 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20121118040644/http://www.sydneycatholic.org/news/latest_news/2012/20121115_453.shtml | archive-date = 18 November 2012 | url-status = dead | df = dmy-all }}</ref> Pell was himself later convicted of child sex offences, but was acquitted by the [[High Court of Australia]] on 7 April 2020.<ref name=\"CNA_Pell\">{{cite web |title=Reports of Pell guilty verdict emerge, despite gag order |url=https://www.catholicnewsagency.com/news/reports-of-pell-guilty-verdict-emerge-despite-gag-order-32220 |website=Catholic News Agency |publisher=Catholic News Agency |accessdate=31 May 2019}}</ref>  The Bishops Conference, established a national co-ordinating body, called the [[Truth, Justice and Healing Council]] to oversee the church's engagement with the Royal Commission and the pastoral and other ramifications that arose from the sexual abuse scandal.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://www.catholic.org.au/acbc-media/media-centre/media-releases-new/1335-announcement-of-chair-and-ceo-of-royal-commission-council-1 |title=Announcement of Chair and CEO of the Catholic Church Council for the Royal Commission|date=12 December 2012|publisher=[[Australian Catholic Bishops Conference]]|accessdate=16 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nOf the 201 Catholic Church authorities surveyed by the Royal Commission, 92 (46%) reported having received at least one claim of child sexual abuse. Overall, some 4,444 claimants alleged incidents of abuse in 4,756 reported claims over the period 1950-2015 (86% of claims related to pre-1990 incidents). The 3,057 claims resulting in a payment for redress amounted to $268 million between 1980 and 2015. Alleged perpetrators were overwhelmingly male (90%) and religious brothers were disproportionally highly responsible (having the most claimants and some 37% of all alleged perpetrators, despite being numerically inferior to priests and religious sisters).  By means of a weighted index, the Commission found that at 75 archdioceses/dioceses and religious institutes with priest members examined, some 7 per cent of priests (who worked in Australia between 1950 and 2009<ref name=\"singledOut\">{{cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2017/12/15/571013476/catholic-church-singled-out-in-australian-sex-abuse-report |title=Catholic Church Singled Out In Australian Sex Abuse Report|author=Neuman, Scott|date=15 December 2017| accessdate = 15 December 2017}}</ref>) were alleged perpetrators (this finding did not represent allegations tested in a court of law).<ref name=\"childabuseroyalcommission.gov.au\"/>  Senior Counsel Gail Furness told the Commission that \"Children were ignored or worse, punished. Allegations were not investigated. Priests and religious leaders were moved. The parishes or communities to which they were moved knew nothing of their past. Documents were not kept or they were destroyed.\"<ref name=aljazzeraabuse>{{cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/02/scale-catholic-church-sex-crimes-revealed-170206135244774.html|title='Shocking' scale of Catholic Church sex crimes revealed|website=www.aljazeera.com}}</ref><ref name=royalabuse>{{cite web|url=https://www.childabuseroyalcommission.gov.au/case-studies/case-study-50-institutional-review-catholic-church-authorities|title=Case Study 50: Institutional review of Catholic Church authorities|date=6 February 2017|website=Royal Commission into Institutional Responses to Child Sexual Abuse}}</ref>  By August 2011, according to [[Broken Rites]], a support and advocacy group for church-related sex abuse victims, there had been over 100 cases in Australia where Catholic priests had been charged for sex offences against minors, as well as others involving non-custodial sentences and inconclusive proceedings.<ref>{{cite web |work=Broken Rites |title=Black Collar Crime in Australia |url=http://brokenrites.alphalink.com.au/nletter/bccrime.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010422203616/http://brokenrites.alphalink.com.au/nletter/bccrime.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=22 April 2001 |date=28 August 2011 |accessdate=18 September 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn 3 June 2019, 18 months after being ordered to do so by the country's Royal Commission into Institutional Child Sexual Abuse, the Australian Catholic Church published its National Catholic Safeguarding Standards.<ref name=ncrstandards>{{cite web|url=https://www.ncronline.org/news/quick-reads/australian-catholic-church-releases-standards-child-protection|title=Australian Catholic Church releases standards for child protection|date=3 June 2019|website=National Catholic Reporter}}</ref> The standards closely parallel the commission's recommendations as well as norms enshrined by the government in the National Principles for Child Safe Organizations, although some provisions were watered down.<ref name=ncrstandards /> One notable alteration concerned the number of hours per year that people should be undergoing professional and pastoral supervision, which was reduced from the recommended 12 hours to six hours.<ref name=ncrstandards />\n\n==Cases==\n\n===Archdiocese of Adelaide===\n{{see also|Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Adelaide}}\nOn 13 September 2011, [[Australian Senate|Senator]] [[Nick Xenophon]] used parliamentary privilege to name an Adelaide priest as the alleged perpetrator of six sexual assaults on [[John Hepworth]] about 50 years earlier. Senator Xenophon alleged that the Vicar-General of Adelaide, Monsignor [[David Cappo]], had been provided with detailed allegations in 2008 but had failed to act upon them, the investigations still being \"at a preliminary stage\" and the priest concerned not being stood down during the investigation.<ref>{{cite news |first=Mark |last=Metherell |title=Senator names priest on 'rape' |work=The Sydney Morning Herald |date=14 September 2011 |url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/senator-names-priest-on-rape-20110913-1k82k.html |accessdate=14 September 2011 }}</ref> Monsignor Cappo subsequently resigned from several governmental positions.<ref>{{cite news | title = David Cappo resigns over John Hepworth case | date = 15 September 2011 | work = news.com.au | url = http://www.news.com.au/breaking-news/sacappo-resigns-over-hepworth-case/story-e6frfku0-1226138126452 | accessdate = 21 February 2012 }}</ref> The Catholic church established a formal independent inquiry, conducted by Michael Abbott,  {{post-nominals|country=AUS|QC}}, found that there was no substance to the allegations.<ref>{{cite news | title = No substance to priest John Hepworth's rape claim - church | date = 28 November 2011 | work = news.com.au | url = http://www.news.com.au/breaking-news/no-substance-to-priest-john-hepworths-rape-claim-church/story-e6frfku0-1226208362977 | accessdate = 21 February 2012 }}</ref>\n\nFather Albert Davis (d. 2007), a member of the Dominican Fathers, was charged in 2006 with 17 incidents of indecent assault involving seven boys at [[Blackfriars Priory School]] between 1956 and 1960. Davis was committed to stand trial in the Adelaide District Court, but he died before proceedings were commenced.<ref>{{cite news | title = Tasmanian priest guilty of abuse, SA accused dies |  work = Catholic News | date = 27 March 2007 | url = http://cathnews.acu.edu.au/703/165.php | accessdate = 19 September 2011 }}</ref>\n\nFather Charles Barnett pleaded guilty in 2009 (after extradition from Indonesia) to three child sex charges for events between 1977 and 1985 at Crystal Brook and Port Pirie.<ref>{{cite news |title=Extradited ex-priest admits child sex |work=ABC News |location=Australia |date=9 September 2009 |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2009-09-08/extradited-ex-priest-admits-child-sex/1421448?section=justin |accessdate=20 September 2011 }}</ref>\n\n===Archdiocese of Sydney===\n{{see also|Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Sydney}}\nIn 2007, Ross Murrin, 52, a former Sydney Catholic school teacher and [[Marist Brothers|Marist brother]], accused of indecently assaulting eight male Year 5 students at a Daceyville school in south-east Sydney in 1974, pleaded guilty to some of the 21 charges.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2007/09/18/2036400.htm |title=Catholic brother to plead guilty to abuse |work=ABC News |location=Australia |date=18 September 2007 |accessdate=18 September 2011 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Fr. Roger Flaherty received a sentence of two years and two weeks in prison five months after pleading guilty to molesting three altar boys in the 1970s and 1980s.<ref name=flahertygone>{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/nsw/paedophile-catholic-priest-aged-72-sentenced-to-two-years-in-prison-20160225-gn3bq7.html|title=Paedophile Catholic priest aged 72 sentenced to two years in prison|first=Tim|last=Barlass|date=25 February 2016|website=The Sydney Morning Herald}}</ref> However, Flaherty's advanced age and poor health allowed him to be eligible for parole six months into his sentence.<ref name=flahertygone /> Former Sydney Archbishop Cardinal [[James Darcy Freeman|James Freeman]] and Auxiliary Bishop Edward Kelly were accused of shielding Flaherty from prosecution when the acts of sex abuse were committed.<ref name=flahertygone />\n\nIn 2017, Fr. Denis Chrysostom Alexander was arrested in Sydney and faces an extradition to [[Scotland]] for sexual and physical abuse he reportedly committed at the former [[Fort Augustus Abbey]] in the 1970s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-01-24/alleged-abusive-priest-arrested-in-sydney/8208706|title=Australian Catholic priest accused of abuse at Scottish school arrested in Sydney|first=Thomas|last=Oriti|date=24 January 2017|website=ABC News}}</ref> The sex abuse investigation against Alexander also resulted in the Archdiocese of Sydney stripping him being of his priestly faculties in Australia by 2013 as well.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-23477335|title=Abuse claims at ex-boarding school|first=Mark|last=Daly|date=29 July 2013|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-highlands-islands-47949648|title=Abuse claim monk 'should return to Scotland'|first=Mark|last=Daly|date=16 April 2019|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Sydney|Archbishop of Sydney]], Cardinal [[George Pell]], was convicted of child sex offences, but was acquitted by the [[High Court of Australia]] in 2020.\n\nIn April 2019, Fr. Anthony Caruana was arrested and charged with sexually abusing five minors, including one male minor, between the years 1982 and 1988 when he was a dormitory manager, rugby coach and band teacher at [[Chevalier College]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/nsw/catholic-priest-charged-over-alleged-child-sex-abuse-at-nsw-school-20190413-p51dt3.html|title=Catholic priest charged over alleged child sex abuse at NSW school|first=Megan Gorrey, Sally|last=Rawsthorne|date=13 April 2019|website=The Sydney Morning Herald}}</ref>\n\n====Diocese of Armidale====\n{{see also|Roman Catholic Diocese of Armidale}}\nThis diocese incorporates 25 parishes and 24 schools within about 90,000&nbsp;km\u00b2<ref>{{cite|url=http://armidale.catholic.org.au/|title=Catholic Diocese of Armidale|work=Catholic Church |location=Australia |date=17 May 2017 |accessdate=17 May 2017 }}</ref> and is clearly, one of, if not the highest density locations of Catholic Child Sexual Abuse in Australia on a per capita basis.  The extraordinary and shocking story of 'Father F', later to be identified as former Armidale local, and former Catholic Priest John Joseph Farrell, was central to the [[ABC Television]] program [[Four Corners (Australian TV program)|Four Corners]] expose \"Unholy Silence\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EI7kMkFEn0g|title=Unholy Silence - Paedophiles in the Catholic Church|via=www.youtube.com}}</ref>  This was first broadcast on Monday 2 July 2012<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/4corners/unholy-silence/4112724|title=Unholy Silence|date=28 June 2012|via=www.abc.net.au}}</ref> and was potentially the final trigger that led to then Prime Minister [[Julia Gillard]] announcing the Royal Commission into Institutional Responses to Child Sexual Abuse.  The reaction of Armidale locals to the program was strong and one of indignation that something should have been done sooner by the Catholic Church.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z_lFsmmPidM|title=Armidale reacts to church abuse investigation|via=www.youtube.com}}</ref> Case Study 44 of the Royal Commission (Held Monday 19 to Thursday 22 September 2016<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.childabuseroyalcommission.gov.au/case-studies/case-study-44-catholic-church-authorities-armidale-and-parramatta|title=Case Study 44: Catholic Church authorities in Armidale and Parramatta|date=12 September 2016|website=Royal Commission into Institutional Responses to Child Sexual Abuse}}</ref>) focused specifically on this case of a former Catholic Priest abusing children over a 20-year period and the alleged cover-up by the Church hierarchy including Father Bernard Flood, Father Richard Gleeson, Monsignor Wayne Peters (Dec), Father Brian Lucas, Monsignor John Usher, Bishop Gerard Hanna (Ret), Bishop Bede Heather (Ret), Bishop Luc Matthys, (most of whom gave evidence to the Royal Commission<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.childabuseroyalcommission.gov.au/sites/default/files/file-list/Case%20Study%2044%20-%20Witness%20list%20-%20Catholic%20Church%20authorities%20in%20Armidale%20and%20Parramatta%20-%20Sydney.pdf?guid=c42216fb-893c-4a72-bb41-2d809b50f86a&type=witnesslistpdf&filename=case-study-44%2C-september-2016%2C-sydney-witness-list&fileextension=pdf |title=CASE STUDY 44: JOHN JOSEPH FARRELL |date=13 September 2016 |website=www.childabuseroyalcommission.gov.au |format=PDF |access-date=2019-09-22}}</ref>), and even Australia's most senior Catholic Cardinal George Pell.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/nsw/royal-commission-monsignor-john-usher-denies-protecting-cardinal-george-pell-20160922-grlrmk.html|title=Royal commission: Monsignor John Usher denies protecting Cardinal George Pell|first=Rachel|last=Browne|date=22 September 2016|website=The Sydney Morning Herald}}</ref>\n\nOn November 1, 2019, former Diocese of Armidale priest David Perrett plead not guilty to 139 charges of child sexual assault at a number of locations, including Armidale, Guyra, Walgett, Moree, Penrith, Bundarra, Lower Creek, and Sawtell between the 1960s and 1990s.<ref>https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-11-01/former-priest-pleads-not-guilty-to-sex-charges/11664202</ref> Perrett, aged 82, had been arrested for these charges and was denied bail in August 2018,<ref>https://www.northerndailyleader.com.au/story/5601642/81yo-retired-priest-refused-bail-on-historical-sex-abuse-charges/</ref> but was later granted bail in April 2019 after he was told he had only six months to a year to live.<ref>https://www.smh.com.au/national/nsw/a-spent-volcano-old-ill-former-priest-bailed-on-131-charges-20190409-p51cip.html</ref>\n\n====Diocese of Maitland-Newcastle====\n{{see also|Roman Catholic Diocese of Maitland-Newcastle|Philip Wilson (bishop)#Allegations of mishandling the reported sexual abuse of children{{!}}Philip Wilson}}\nThe diocese has been referred to as the \"epicentre of Catholic clerical sexual abuse in Australia\"<ref name=Crittenden>{{cite news |first1=Stephen |last1=Crittenden |first2=Suzanne |last2=Smith |title=Archbishop's handling of abuse claims challenged |work=ABC News |location=Australia |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2010/05/17/2901859.htm |date=18 May 2010 |accessdate=16 September 2011}}</ref> due to a number of paedophile priests with extensive abuse records being jailed since 1997, a dedicated clergy abuse police strikeforce (Strike Force Lantle) having laid more than 170 abuse charges.<ref name=\"abc.net.au\">{{cite news |title=Newcastle Catholic Bishop supports abuse inquiry |work=ABC News |location=Australia |date=26 July 2012 |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2012-07-26/newcastle-catholic-bishop-supports-abuse-inquiry/4157078 |accessdate=28 July 2012 }}</ref> Convicted abusers include Father Vincent Ryan (a $6&nbsp;million compensation payout to victims, setting a record for the Catholic Church in Australia), Father David O'Hearn (serving a 23-year sentence)<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2016-08-22/hunter-catholic-priest-david-ohearn-sentenced-over-child-sex/7771798|title=Hunter Catholic priest David O'Hearn sentenced to more than five years over child sex offences|author=Brown, Michelle|work=ABC News|location=Australia|date=22 August 2016|access-date=22 May 2018}}</ref> and Father James Fletcher (died in jail in 2006).<ref>{{cite news|title=Cases against clergy in Maitland-Newcastle Diocese |work=ABC News |location=Australia |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/infographics/clergy-questioned/ |date=16 May 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100521235945/http://www.abc.net.au/news/infographics/clergy-questioned/ |archivedate=21 May 2010 }}</ref>\n\nJohn Sidney Denham pleaded guilty to 29 child sex charges involving 27 boys under his care while a priest in Newcastle in the 1970s.<ref>{{cite news |title=Priest sex abuse sentence delayed |work=ABC News |location=Australia |date=5 February 2010 |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2010/02/05/2811371.htm |accessdate=5 February 2010 }}</ref> It was alleged that the Archbishop of Adelaide, [[Philip Wilson (bishop)|Philip Wilson]], knew about clerical sexual abuse when serving in the New South Wales' diocese of Maitland-Newcastle in the late 1970s and 1980s.<ref name=Crittenden /> On 27 July 2012, John Pirona was found dead in his car five days after leaving a letter ending \"too much pain\", this referring to his abuse by a paedophile priest in 1979 when Pirona was 12, the event occurring a year after Maitland-Newcastle bishop Leo Clarke was informed that the priest was a sex offender.<ref>{{cite news|author=McCarthy, Joanne|title=Abused Man Takes His Life|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|date=28 July 2012|page=3}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 July 2012, NSW Police in Strike Force Lantle announced they would be providing prosecutors with evidence that Father Brian Lucas, general secretary of the Australian Catholic Bishops Conference, Archbishop Wilson of Adelaide and Michael Malone, retired Bishop of Maitland-Newcastle, had committed the offence of concealing a serious crime under s316 of the ''[[Crimes Act 1900]]'' (NSW) in concealing child sexual abuse by the priest Denis McAlinden (now deceased) in the Maitland-Newcastle diocese. The evidence includes an admission by then Maitland-Newcastle bishop, Leo Clarke, to McAlinden that \"your good name will be protected by the confidential nature of the process\" despite \"your admission to Father Brian Lucas and other evidence\" and a letter from the late Maitland-Newcastle monsignor Patrick Cotter to Bishop Clarke that McAlinden \"feels no such inclination towards mature females but towards the little ones. I have never heard of this condition before and knowing Father McAlinden as we do, we do not think it can be real serious.\"<ref>{{cite news|author1=McCarthy, Joanne|author2=Besser, Linton|title=Police Move on Priests Over Abuse 'Cover-Up'|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|date=31 July 2012|page=1 |url=https://www.smh.com.au/nsw/police-move-on-priests-over-abuse-coverup-20120730-23aba.html|accessdate=31 July 2012}}</ref> In November 2012 the [[Premier of New South Wales]], [[Barry O'Farrell]], ordered a special commission of inquiry into allegations of sexual abuse by Catholic clergy in this diocese and whether the church had hindered police investigations.<ref>{{cite news|authorlink=Imre Salusinszky|author=Salusinszky, Imre|title=Farrell orders inquiry into Catholic church sex abuse investigations|work=[[The Australian]]|date=9 November 2012|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/nation/ofarrell-orders-inquiry-into-catholic-church-sex-abuse-investigations/story-e6frg6nf-1226513826422 |accessdate=12 November 2012 }}</ref> Presided over by [[Margaret Cunneen]] {{post-nominals|country=AUS|SC}}, she reported her findings to the [[Governor of New South Wales]], [[Marie Bashir]], on 30 May 2014.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-05-30/hunter-child-abuse-special-commission-of-inquiry-clears-police/5488942|title=Special Commission of Inquiry clears police, finds whistleblower Peter Fox 'not credible' over child abuse cover-up claims|last1=Ansari|first1=Tahmina|work=[[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]] |location=Australia |date=30 May 2014|accessdate=17 April 2015}}</ref> On 22 May 2018, the Newcastle Local Court found Wilson guilty of the charge of failing to report allegations of child sexual abuse by Fletcher in 1976.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-05-22/adelaide-archbishop-found-guilty-of-concealing-child-abuse/9783612 |title=Archbishop of Adelaide Philip Wilson found guilty of covering up child sexual abuse |first=Nancy |last=Notzon |newspaper=ABC News |accessdate=22 May 2018 |date=22 May 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"verdict\">{{cite news|title=Catholic Archbishop found guilty of covering up child sexual abuse|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-05-22/adelaide-archbishop-found-guilty-of-concealing-child-abuse/9783612|accessdate=22 May 2018|work=ABC News|date=22 May 2018|language=en-AU}}</ref>  Wilson was given a maximum sentence of 12 months in detention for concealing child sexual abuse in the 1970s.<ref>{{cite news|title=Archbishop Philip Wilson sentenced for concealing child sex abuse |work=BBC |location=Australia |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-australia-44692396/ |date=3 July 2018 }}</ref>  On 6 December 2018, Wilson was acquitted of all the charges of which he had previously been found guilty. The Director of Public Prosecutions had been reported to be considering a challenge in the Supreme Court of New South Wales but on 20 December, announced that there were no reasonable prospects of success of appeal on errors of law.\n\nOn 15 February 2017 it was reported that The Catholic Church in Australia had secretly paid the equivalent of $276.1&nbsp;million in compensation to thousands of people sexually abused as children by priests and religious brothers.<ref name=settlementoz>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2017/feb/16/australian-catholic-church-has-paid-276m-to-abuse-victims-so-far-inquiry-shows|title=Australian Catholic church has paid $276m to abuse victims so far, inquiry shows|agency=[[Australian Associated Press]]|author=|work=[[Guardian Australia]]|date=16 February 2017|access-date=22 May 2018}}</ref> Between 1980 and 2015, the Christian Brothers, which operated a number of residential facilities, made the highest number of payments at 763, totaling $48.5&nbsp;million.<ref name=settlementoz />  Most reported incidents of sex abuse occurred between 1950 and 1989.<ref name=settlementoz />  Some reported incidents occurred as early as the 1920s and the latest after 2010.<ref name=settlementoz />\n\nIn May 2019, Fr. Vincent Gerald Ryan, who had previously served 14 years in jail for sex abusing for abusing 34 boys from 1973 to 1991, was jailed for at least 14 months for sex abuse he committed against two altar boys during this timeframe which weren't prosecuted.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://7news.com.au/news/crime/former-catholic-priest-jailed-for-sexual-abuse-of-two-altar-boys-in-hunter-region-c-126587|title='Burn in hell': Former priest Vincent Ryan to go back behind bars|date=22 May 2019|website=7NEWS.com.au}}</ref>\n\n====Diocese of Wagga Wagga====\n{{see also|Roman Catholic Diocese of Wagga Wagga}}\nIn 2002, Vincent Kieran Kiss, 70, pleaded guilty in the Sydney District Court for sex crimes against four teenage boys, aged 13 to 17, between 1966 and 1973 at locations including [[Albury, New South Wales|Albury]], [[Yass, New South Wales|Yass]] and Sydney. Kiss was the Diocesan Director of Youth in Wagga Wagga at the time of the offences and the four victims were members of the Young Christian Students Association.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2002/08/07/1028157962938.html |title=Father Kiss pleads guilty to sex charges |work=The Age |location=Australia |date=8 August 2002 |accessdate=18 September 2011 }}</ref>\n\n====Diocese of Wollongong====\n{{see also|Roman Catholic Diocese of Wollongong}}\nIn 1993, the ''[[Illawarra Mercury]]'' alleged that Gwynneville parish priest Father Peter Lewis Comensoli and Brother Michael Evans had been involved in the sexual abuse of boys.<ref>{{cite journal |work=PANPA Bulletin |date=September 2005 |pages=56\u201357 |url=http://espace.library.uq.edu.au/eserv/UQ:8806/rk_panpa_0905.pdf |format=PDF |title=Guts-and-glory, murder and more during the Mercury\u2019s 150 years |author=Kirkpatrick, Rod |accessdate=18 September 2011 }}</ref><ref name=\"WonderfulWollongong\">{{cite news |url=http://www.abc.net.au/rn/talks/bbing/stories/s328.htm |series=Background Briefing |title=Wonderful Wollongong |work=ABC Radio National |location=Australia |date=30 August 1998 |author=Robinson, Gareth |format=transcript |access-date=16 May 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090216181309/http://www.abc.net.au/rn/talks/bbing/stories/s328.htm |archive-date=16 February 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Comensoli was jailed and was later named during the [[Royal Commission into the New South Wales Police Service|Wood Royal Commission]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.illawarramercury.com.au/news/local/news/general/underbelly-3-a-tale-of-wollongongs-darkest-hour/1531391.aspx?storypage=0 |title=Underbelly 3: A tale of Wollongong's darkest hour |work=Illawarra Mercury |first=Jodie |last=Minus |date=4 June 2009 |accessdate=18 September 2011 }}</ref> Evans committed suicide.<ref name=\"WonderfulWollongong\" />\n\nIn 1996 Father John Gerard Nestor was charged with the 1991 indecent assault of a 15-year-old altar boy. Nestor was initially convicted by a Local Court magistrate and sentenced to a 16 months gaol term which was overturned on an \"all points\" appeal to the District Court. The case ended suddenly when prosecution witnesses were caught in contradictions, Judge Phelen stating that the supposed victim seemed to have difficulty \"distinguishing fact from imagination\". Nestor went on to work as a priest for a number of years in senior appointments. After engaging in secular employment he was [[Loss of clerical state (Catholic Church)|laicised]] in 2009.<ref name=\"age abbott\">{{cite news|url=http://news.theage.com.au/breaking-news-national/abbott-vouched-for-priest-later-struck-off-20130206-2dxoh.html | location=Melbourne | work=The Age | title=Abbott vouched for priest later struck off |date=6 February 2013 |accessdate=15 May 2015 |author= }}</ref> The former Australian prime minister and leader of the [[Australian Liberal Party]], [[Tony Abbott]], provided a character reference for Nestor's trial describing him as \"an upright and virtuous man whom he had known since 1984 while studying at Sydney's St Patrick's Seminary to become a priest\".<ref name=\"age abbott\" /> The ''[[Illawarra Mercury]]'' reported lawyer Chris Murphy suggesting that the Royal Commission into Institutional Responses to Child Sexual Abuse investigate the case of Nestor.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.illawarramercury.com.au/story/1289070/royal-commission-should-examine-nestor-case/ |title=Royal commission 'should examine Nestor case'  |work=[[Illawarra Mercury]] |date=8 February 2013 |accessdate=15 May 2015 |author=Osborne, Paul |agency=AAP }}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Kelvin Gerald Sharkey, 83, was sentenced in the Wollongong District Court to at least 15 months jail for sexually abusing an altar boy on three occasions between 1969 and 1975 when Sharkey was parish priest of St John Vianney's Church at Fairy Meadow and at St Bernard's Church at Batemans Bay.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2010/04/30/2886983.htm |title=Church to deregister sex abuse ex-priest |work=ABC News |location=Australia |date=30 April 2010 |accessdate=18 September 2011 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Marist Brother and former principal of the Mary Immaculate Catholic Parish Primary School in the Sydney suburb of Eagle Vale, plead guilty to four counts of sexually abusing a minor.<ref name=schooldaysconvict>{{cite web|url=https://cruxnow.com/global-church/2018/02/06/australian-bishop-apologizes-school-abuse-calls-victims-come-forward/ |title=Australian bishop apologizes for school abuse, calls on victims to come forward |publisher=Cruxnow.com |date=2018-02-06 |accessdate=2019-09-22}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, then Bishop [[Peter Ingham (bishop)|Peter Ingham]] issued an apology and acknowledged the history of sex abuse at various Catholic schools in the Diocese of Wollongong.<ref name=schooldaysconvict />\n\nIn March 2019, Father Ron Peters, who was formerly listed as the \"Dean and Adiministrator\" of the Diocese of Wollongong,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/dutch.in.wollongong/posts/524194251115327|title=Dutch in Wollongong|website=www.facebook.com}}</ref><ref>[http://www.lumenchristi.org.au/index.php/RonPeters ]{{dead link|date=September 2019}}</ref> was charged with sex abuse.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.camdenadvertiser.com.au/story/5969884/former-campbelltown-priest-charged-with-indecent-assaults-on-boy/|title=Former Campbelltown priest charged with indecent assaults on boy|first=Cydonee|last=Mardon|date=22 March 2019|website=Camden-Narellan Advertiser}}</ref>\n\n====Diocese of Bathurst====\n{{see also|Roman Catholic Diocese of Bathurst in Australia|St Stanislaus College (Bathurst)}}\nSt Stanislaus College Bathurst in the 1970s and 1980s was referred to by an anonymous former student as a \"pedophile paradise\" due to the abusive activities of priests there.<ref>{{cite news |first=Damien |last=Murphy |work=The Sydney Morning Herald |date=6 September 2008 |title=Old boy calls school a pedophile paradise |url=https://www.smh.com.au/news/national/old-boy-calls-school-a-pedophile-paradise/2008/09/05/1220121526764.html |accessdate=22 September 2011 }}</ref> William Stanley Irwin, 55, for instance, a former Catholic brother, was convicted on 31 March 2011 by a jury in the Sydney District Court on two counts of gross indecency on a male under the age of 18 at [[St Stanislaus College (Bathurst)|St Stanislaus' College]] in Bathurst in the mid-1980s. Having been asked by the boy's parents to counsel him in relation to prior sexual abuse, Irwin kissed the youth and initiated mutual masturbation when the pair stayed at the boarding school overnight during a road trip in 1986. Irwin was later a dormitory master at St Stanislaus' for two years and a chaplain and teacher at [[St Aloysius' College (Sydney)|St Aloysius' College]] at Milsons Point.<ref>{{cite news |last=Courts |first=Louise Hall |title=Catholic brother abused boy he was counselling |work= The Sydney Morning Herald |date=1 April 2011 |url=https://www.smh.com.au/nsw/catholic-brother-abused-boy-he-was-counselling-20110331-1cnhj.html |accessdate=1 April 2011 }}</ref>\n\nKevin Francis Phillips, similarly, pleaded guilty in a Sydney District Court on 3 December 2010 to four counts of gross indecency with a child under the age of 18. Phillips was sentenced on 21 April 2011 to a total of 15 months jail. On the first three counts, he was sentenced to a concurrent term of nine months starting on 21 April 2011 and expiring on 20 January 2012. On the final charge of gross indecency by a male with a male under 18 years, Phillips was sentenced to a term of nine months to start on 21 October 2011 and expiring on 20 July 2012 with a non-parole period of three months.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.smh.com.au/nsw/former-priest-denies-assault-after-channelling-voice-of-dead-20101115-17ufc.html |agency=AAP |title=Sixth teacher charged over sex abuse |work=The Australian |date=5 May 2009 |accessdate=22 November 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"SMHPhillips\">{{cite news |url=https://www.smh.com.au/nsw/stannies-priest-convicted-of-abuse-20101203-18ju2.html |author=Marr, David |authorlink=David Marr (journalist) |title=Stannies priest convicted of abuse |work=The Sydney Morning Herald |date=4 December 2010 |accessdate=4 December 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.centralwesterndaily.com.au/news/local/news/general/exstannies-priest-jailed/2158818.aspx |title=Ex-Stannies priest jailed |work=Central Western Daily |location=Australia |date=11 May 2011 |accessdate=11 May 2011}}</ref>\n\nBrian Joseph Spillane also was convicted on 30 November 2010 on nine counts of indecent assault against three girls aged between eight and seventeen while he was based in Sydney in about 1979, a Vincentian priest at that time. During bail proceedings it was heard that Spillane faced a further 135 charges relating to alleged offences against boys at St Stanislaus' College whilst Spillaine was chaplain. These latter charges were expected to be heard in four more trials that were expected to last until late 2011. Spillaine was refused bail.<ref name=\"SMHGodHelpMe\">{{cite news |url=https://www.smh.com.au/nsw/god-help-me-former-priest-found-guilty-of-child-abuse-20101130-18fe9.html |last=Marr |first=David |title=God help me: former priest found guilty of child abuse |work=The Sydney Morning Herald |date=1 December 2010 |accessdate=4 December 2010 }}</ref> After a court-ordered media blackout was lifted, in place since 2013, it was reported in 2016 that Spillane was convicted of assaults on five St Stanislaus' College students after a trial in 2013, and in 2015 he pleaded guilty to assaults on four boys at the school in the late 1980s. It was reported that during 2016 Spillane was convicted of attacks on five students between 1974 and 1990.<ref name=\"SMH2016\">{{cite news |url=https://www.smh.com.au/nsw/notorious-paedophile-brian-spillane-convicted-of-more-stannies-sex-assaults-20161205-gt4hh1.html |author=Gardiner, Stephanie |title=Notorious paedophile Brian Spillane convicted of more Stannies sex assaults |work=The Sydney Morning Herald |date=5 December 2016 |accessdate=10 December 2016 }}</ref> Spillane, who is currently in custody, was sentenced in February 2017 to an additional nine years in prison, and is not eligible for parole.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-02-16/paedophile-priest-jailed-for-nine-years/8275458|title=Paedophile priest Brian Spillane jailed for nine years|first=Sean|last=Rubinsztein-Dunlop|date=16 February 2017|website=ABC News}}</ref>\n\n==== Diocese of Parramatta ====\nIn 1992, after allegations arose that a priest had been sexually abusing some of his parishioners, a meeting was held between the accused priest and three senior members of clergy. As a result of the meeting the priest was banned from conducting Mass, but was otherwise permitted to continue serving as a priest. The priest was laicised in 2005. In 2012, allegations arose through the ''[[Four Corners (Australian TV program)|Four Corners]]'' television program that the priest admitted to child sexual abuse at the 1992 meeting, and that the senior clergy present chose not to report the allegations to police. Cardinal [[George Pell]] subsequently denied that the priest admitted to sexual abuse at the meeting.<ref>{{cite news |last=Allard |first=Tom |date=4 July 2012 |title=Calls for royal commission over alleged cover-up of Catholic abuse |url=https://www.smh.com.au/opinion/political-news/calls-for-royal-commission-over-alleged-coverup-of-catholic-abuse-20120703-21flg.html |accessdate=6 July 2012 |work=The Sydney Morning Herald}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2010, Fr. Robert MacGregor Fuller began serving a 6-18 month sentence months after pleading guilty to sending both a sexually lurid video broadcast of himself and sexually lurid text messages to a 13-year-old girl in the summer of 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2010-02-24/priest-jailed-but-celibacy-vow-cruel/342040 |title=Priest jailed but celibacy vow &#039;cruel&#039; |publisher=Abc.net.au |date=2010-02-24 |accessdate=2019-09-22}}</ref>\n\n===Archdiocese of Melbourne===\n{{Main|Sexual abuse scandal in Melbourne archdiocese}}\n{{update|section|date=April 2020}}\nThe Chief Commissioner of Victoria Police in a submission to a parliamentary inquiry established in April 2012 stated that Melbourne archdiocese's ''Melbourne Response'' process, under which victims may not be legally represented appeared to \"be a de facto substitute for criminal justice\" that was detrimental to prosecuting suspected sexual criminals.<ref name=\"Jane Lee 2012\">{{cite news |author=Lee, Jane |title=Police Slam Catholic Church. Investigations impeded, accused abusers moved on, inquiry told |work=[[The Age]] |date=11 October 2012 |url= |accessdate= |page= }}</ref> He noted that though the ''Melbourne Response'' states on its website that in the past 14 years the church has compensated 300 people as victims of sexual abuse and identified 86 offenders of whom 60 were priests, not one complainant was referred to Victoria Police.<ref name=\"Jane Lee 2012\"/> The report stated that the process of moving offenders to other positions in the church restricted capacity to bring them to account and promoted a culture of secrecy that hindered more victims speaking out. The ''Melbourne Response's'' system, the report states, has outdated process that include requiring victims to confront alleged offenders.<ref name=\"Jane Lee 2012\"/>\n\nNotable cases have included: [[Michael Charles Glennon]] - sentenced to 22 years jail with a non-parole period of 15 years for 23 offences against children, including rape, indecent assault, gross indecency, sexually penetrating a child under the age of 16 and sexually penetrating a child under the age of 10.;<ref>{{cite news |author=Topsfield, Jewel |date=10 October 2003 |title=Notorious pedophile guilty |work=[[Herald Sun]] |url=http://www.poynter.org/dg.lts/id.46/aid.50861/column.htm |accessdate=11 December 2006 |publisher=The Poynter Institute |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060521203333/http://www.poynter.org/dg.lts/id.46/aid.50861/column.htm# |archive-date=21 May 2006 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> David Daniel - sentenced to six years jail with a non-parole period of four years and six months for molesting four boys, a girl and an adult male;<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.starnewsgroup.com.au/story/46544 |work=Mountain Views Mail |title=Hear the truth |first=Kath |last=Gannaway |date=7 August 2007 |accessdate=18 September 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071028222634/http://www.starnewsgroup.com.au/story/46544 |archivedate=28 October 2007 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and Wilfred James Baker -  sentenced to four years in prison (parole after 2 years) for 16 counts of indecent assault and one of gross indecency, involving eight boys, aged 10 to 13, over a 20-year period between 1960 and 1979.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2002/05/03/1019441435037.html |title=Speak no evil |author=Ellingsen, Peter |date=4 May 2002 |work=The Age |accessdate=30 January 2012 |location=Melbourne}}</ref> Three priests, Michael Aulsebrook, Frank Klep and David Rapson, were investigated and prosecuted for sexual abuse which took place at Rupertswood College Sunbury in the 1990s.<ref>{{cite news |last=Lowe |first= Adrian |date=23 August 2011 |title=Sunbury priest jailed for sex abuse |work=The Age |location=Australia |url=http://www.theage.com.au/victoria/sunbury-priest-jailed-for-sex-abuse-20110822-1j6p5.html |accessdate=17 September 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Stayner |first=Guy |date=25 June 2004 |title=Paedophile priest arrested in Melbourne |work=Lateline |location=Australia |url=http://www.abc.net.au/lateline/content/2004/s1140908.htm |accessdate=17 September 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121113093957/http://www.abc.net.au/lateline/content/2004/s1140908.htm |archive-date=13 November 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Daly |first=Martin |date=24 July 2004 |title=Priest used drink on boys: victim |work=The Age |location=Australia |url=http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2004/07/23/1090464864785.html |accessdate=17 September 2011 }}</ref> Rapson was jailed in 2013 for at least 13 years, with the possibility of parole after 10 years, for molesting 8 students at a Catholic school in Melbourne between 1973 and 1990.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/nation/ex-priest-david-edwin-rapson-jailed-for-heartless-sex-abuse-of-students/news-story/415a0131067d8ecf5d72e3c698008a6a|title=Ex-priest David Edwin Rapson jailed for 'heartless' sex abuse of students|author=Pia Akerman|newspaper=The Australian|date=October 17, 2013|accessdate=February 28, 2019}}</ref> Kelp was jailed for 10 and a half years in 2014 after he pleaded guilty to 15 sex offences involving many boys, including siblings at the school aged between 11 and 15, between the 1970s and 1980s and will be eligible for parole six and a half years into his sentence.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-05-26/former-priest-frank-klep-sentenced-to-10-years-in-prison/5477560|title=Frank Klep, former Victorian Catholic priest and teacher at Salesian College, sentenced to 10 years in prison|author=Peta Crayon|publisher=ABC|date=May 26, 2014|accessdate=February 28, 2019}}</ref> Aulsebrook, who was convicted in a retrial, received a sentence on 7 and a half years in 2018 for raping a 12-year-old boy at the Salesian College boarding school in 1988 and will be eligible for parole four and half years in his sentence.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/ex-priest-who-drugged-and-raped-12-year-old-boy-gets-reduced-jail-time-20180803-p4zvcf.html|title=Ex-priest who drugged and raped 12-year-old boy gets reduced jail time|author=Amber Wilson|newspaper=The Age|date=August 3, 2018|accessdate=February 28, 2019}}</ref> Former Melbourne Archbishop and former high ranking Roman Curia official Cardinal [[George Pell]] was sent to jail on 27 February 2019, two months after being convicted of molesting two choir boys.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.9news.com.au/national/george-pell-conviction-child-sex-offences-first-night-in-prison-melbourne-cardinal-pell-news/e3c12c46-159a-430c-b7e7-3fa1f91b6396|title=Pell wakes up in \u2018Boneyard\u2019 prison after child sex offences conviction|website=www.9news.com.au}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ncronline.org/news/accountability/cardinal-pell-jailed-australia-ahead-march-13-sentencing|title=Cardinal Pell jailed in Australia ahead of March 13 sentencing|date=27 February 2019|website=National Catholic Reporter}}</ref> Judge Peter Kidd sentenced Pell on 13 March 2019 to serve six years in jail, with three years and eight months non-parole period.<ref>{{cite news |title=George Pell to be sentenced for child sex abuse |url=https://www.9news.com.au/2019/03/13/08/57/george-pell-sentencing-child-sex-abuse-live-coverage-catholic-church-news-melbourne |work=9News |date=13 March 2019 |accessdate=13 March 2019 }}</ref> In August 2019, the [[Victorian Court of Appeal]] rejected an Pell's appeal to have his convictions overturned.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/live/2019/aug/21/cardinal-george-pell-appeal-sexual-assault-conviction |title=Cardinal Pell likely to be stripped of Order of Australia \u2013 as it happened |work=[[Guardian Australia]] |date=21 August 2019 |access-date=22 September 2019 |author=McGown, Michael }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/australasia/cardinal-george-pell-child-sex-abuse-conviction-upheld-australia-catholic-church-vatican-court-a9072406.html |title=Cardinal George Pell has child sex abuse convictions upheld by Australian court |author=Austin, Henry |work=[[The Independent]] |location=United Kingdom |date=21 August 2019 |access-date=22 September 2019 }}</ref> Pell has since sought leave to have the matter heard in the [[High Court of Australia|High Court]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-09-17/george-pell-to-appeal-to-the-high-court/11437796 |title=George Pell seeks leave to appeal child sex abuse convictions in High Court |first=Sarah |last=Farnsworth |work=[[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]] |date=17 September 2019 |access-date=22 September 2019}}</ref> On 7 April 2020, Pell won his appeal with the Australian High Court and soon afterwards released from prison after serving 13 months of his six year prison sentence.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/cardinal-george-pell-be-released-prison-after-australia-s-high-n1178036|title=Cardinal George Pell out of prison after Australia's High Court overturns abuse convictions|author=Phil Helsel and The Associated Press|publisher=NBC News|date=7 April 2020|accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Diocese of Ballarat====\n{{see also|Roman Catholic Diocese of Ballarat}}\nThe [[Royal Commission into Institutional Responses to Child Sexual Abuse#Catholic Church authorities in Ballarat|Royal Commission into Institutional Responses to Child Sexual Abuse]] final report published on 15 December 2017 found that 139 people made a claim of child sexual abuse to the Diocese of Ballarat between 1980 and 2015 and that there was 21 alleged perpetrators identified in claims. Of the 21 alleged and convicted perpetrators 17 were priests which is 8.7% of the priests who ministered during this period.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.childabuseroyalcommission.gov.au/sites/default/files/final_report_-_volume_16_religious_institutions_book_2.pdf|title=Final Report: Volume 16, Religious institutions Book 2|last=Commonwealth of Australia|date=December 2017|website=Royal Commission into Institutional Responses to Child Sexual Abuse|page=106}}</ref>\n\nThe Royal Commissions final report of Catholic Church authorities in Ballarat was released on 6 December.<ref name=\"Gemma.Choy\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.childabuseroyalcommission.gov.au/media-releases/report-catholic-church-authorities-ballarat-released|title=Report into Catholic Church authorities in Ballarat released {{!}} Royal Commission into Institutional Responses to Child Sexual Abuse|last=Gemma.Choy|date=2017-12-06|work=Royal Commission into Institutional Responses to Child Sexual Abuse|access-date=2017-12-16|language=en}}</ref> The Commission found that [[Ronald Mulkearns|Bishop Mulkearns]] failed to take action \"Bishop Mulkearns again was derelict in his duty in failing to take any effective action to have (infamous paedophile Gerald) Ridsdale referred to police and to restrict Ridsdale's contact with children\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thecourier.com.au/story/5103641/we-failed-and-we-are-sorry-church-responds-to-scathing-report/?cs=62|title=We failed and we are sorry: church responds to scathing report|last=Wrigley|first=Brendan|date=2017-12-06|work=The Courier|access-date=2017-12-16|language=en}}</ref> The Commission pointed out to the structure of the Diocese, culture and governance, concluding: \u201cThe most likely explanation for the conduct of Bishop Mulkearns and other senior clergy in the Diocese was that they were trying to minimise the risk of scandal and protect the reputation of the Catholic Church.\" The Melbourne report found that former Ballarat Diocese [[Peter Connors|Bishop Peter Connors]] was part of a culture that practiced \"using oblique or euphemistic language in correspondence and records concerning complaints of child sexual abuse\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thecourier.com.au/story/5102536/royal-commission-slams-former-ballarat-bishop-in-melbourne-report/?cs=62|title=Royal Commission slams former Ballarat Bishop in Melbourne report|last=Wrigley|first=Brendan|date=2017-12-05|work=The Courier|access-date=2017-12-16|language=en}}</ref>\n\nBelow are some extracts from the conclusion of the Royal Commission into Institutional Responses to Child Sexual Abuse's report into Case Study 28 \u2013 Catholic Church authorities in Ballarat:<blockquote>This case study exposed a catastrophic failure in the leadership of the Diocese and ultimately in the structure and culture of the Church over decades to effectively respond to the sexual abuse of children by its priests. That failure led to the suffering and often irreparable harm to children, their families and the wider community. That harm could have been avoided if the Church had acted in the interests of children rather than in its own interests.</blockquote><blockquote>Euphemistic and elliptical language was often used in correspondence and minutes to mask the true nature of the conduct discussed. There was repeated reference to \u2018pressures\u2019, \u2018strains\u2019 and unspecified \u2018problems\u2019. On occasions, records were deliberately not made or kept or were destroyed.</blockquote><blockquote>The result of these inexcusable failures was that more children were sexually abused by Catholic clergy in the Diocese. There was a catastrophic institutional failure which resulted in many children being sexually abused. We heard about the devastating, often lifelong, consequences in the lives of those children. The welfare of children was not the primary concern of Bishop Mulkearns and other senior members of the Diocese when responding to complaints and allegation of child sexual abuse against their priests. There is no doubt it should have been.<ref name=\"Gemma.Choy\"/></blockquote>The report on Ballarat also described the impact it had on victims. One section outlines suicide and premature death caused from the abuse. One victim said<blockquote>Newspapers don\u2019t report suicides, so the public doesn\u2019t hear about the broken families and their shattered lives, about the unseen impact of institutional child sexual abuse. Children are left behind and they don\u2019t understand why. It doesn\u2019t end when the abuse ends.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.childabuseroyalcommission.gov.au/sites/default/files/case_study_28_-_findings_report_-_catholic_church_authorities_in_ballarat_catholic_church_authorities_in_ballarat2.pdf|title=Royal Commission into Institutional Responses to Child Sexual Abuse: Catholic Church authorities in Ballarat - Report of Case Study No. 28|website=Royal Commission into Institutional Responses to Child Sexual Abuse|pages=433\u2013436}}</ref></blockquote>Other harms are outlined. Another victim outlines the general harm in the Ballarat community:<blockquote>Such chronic sexual abuse in the Ballarat community has led to a large number of men who are not able to be productive members of society and in neglect have become either emotional, social or financial burdens upon the community.<ref name=\":0\" /></blockquote>One victim who told their story to the Royal Commission was Paul Levey was sent to live with Ridsdale at the age of 14 at the presbytery in Mortlake.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-3472019/The-disturbing-picture-vile-paedophile-Gerald-Ridsdale-sitting-helpless-14-year-old-victim-Paul-Levey.html|title=The picture of paedophile Gerald Ridsdale with a 14-year-old victim|work=Mail Online|access-date=2017-12-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.standard.net.au/story/5103743/claims-of-sexual-abuse-at-south-west-parishes-fell-on-deaf-ears-commission-finds/|title=Claims of sexual abuse at south-west parishes fell on deaf ears, Commission finds|last=Patterson|first=Andrew Thomson and Monique|date=2017-12-06|work=The Standard|access-date=2017-12-29|language=en}}</ref> The Levey said he was \"sexually abused all the time just about every day\" and the Commission heard evidence that Ronald Mulkearns was among a number of clergy who knew Ridsdale had a boy living with him, but failed to intervene.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/audio/2017/dec/11/the-reckoning-part-1-david-marr-on-the-road-to-the-child-sexual-abuse-commission-podcast|title=The Reckoning part one: the road to the royal commission \u2013 podcast {{!}} David Marr|last=Marr|first=David|date=2017-12-11|work=The Guardian|access-date=2017-12-29|last2=Martignoni|first2=Miles|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|last3=Davey|first3=Melissa}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/abuse-royal-commission-george-pell-must-have-known-says-ridsdale-victim-20160301-gn7g2l.html|title=Abuse royal commission: George Pell must have known, says Ridsdale victim|last=Cunningham|first=Melissa|date=2016-03-02|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=2017-12-29|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/victoria/ballarat-dioceses-catastrophic-failure-led-to-more-abuse-commission-finds-20171206-gzztn4.html|title=Ballarat diocese's 'catastrophic' failure led to more abuse, commission finds|last=Cunningham|first=Melissa|date=2017-12-07|work=The Age|access-date=2017-12-29|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.traumainreligion.com/paul_levey0.php|title=About my life and my abuse by the Catholic paedophile priest Gerald Francis Ridsdale|website=www.traumainreligion.com|access-date=2017-12-29}}</ref> The commission found that Mulkearns \"ignored\" pleas from Paul Levey's mother who was \"concerned about the situation and sought his assistance\" even though \"By this time, Bishop Mulkearns knew of Ridsdale\u2019s admission of offending against boys.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2017/dec/06/catholic-bishop-cared-little-for-children-and-left-them-in-danger-royal-commission-finds|title=Catholic bishop cared little for children and left them in danger, royal commission finds|last=Davey|first=Melissa|date=2017-12-06|work=The Guardian|access-date=2017-12-29|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> The Commission stated that Bishop Mulkearns\u2019 response to Paul Levey living with Ridsdale in the Mortlake presbytery \"demonstrated a total absence of concern for the welfare of that boy\".<ref name=\":02\">{{cite web|url=https://www.childabuseroyalcommission.gov.au/sites/default/files/case_study_28_-_findings_report_-_catholic_church_authorities_in_ballarat_catholic_church_authorities_in_ballarat2.pdf|title=Royal Commission into Institutional Responses to Child Sexual Abuse: Catholic Church authorities in Ballarat - Report of Case Study No. 28|website=Royal Commission into Institutional Responses to Child Sexual Abuse|page=318}}</ref> The Royal Commission into Institutional Responses to Child Sexual Abuse found that the then Bishop of Ballarat Diocese, [[James O'Collins]], had received a complaint in the 1960s that Father Gerald Ridsdale had sexually abused a boy but did not take action.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-08-06/catholic-church-ballarat-diocese-abuse-compensation-claim/8766482|title='No moral compass': Priest's abuse victim slams church over compo dispute|date=2017-08-06|work=ABC News|access-date=2017-12-22|language=en-AU}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.childabuseroyalcommission.gov.au/sites/default/files/final_report_-_volume_16_religious_institutions_book_2.pdf|title=Royal Commission into Institutional Responses to Child Sexual Abuse: Final Report: Volume 16, Religious institutions Book 2|website=Royal Commission into Institutional Responses to Child Sexual Abuse|page=127}}</ref> The royal commission was also told Bishop [[Ronald Mulkearns]] knew in 1975 that Ridsdale had abused boys and again did nothing to stop the abuse from occurring.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.news.com.au/national/courts-law/vile-paedophile-gerald-ridsdale-will-give-evidence-at-royal-commission-today/news-story/63054c92d762e9c3d53629b8da59ccab|title=Paedo Ridsdale: \u2018I went haywire with altar boys\u2019|work=NewsComAu|access-date=2017-12-22}}</ref>\n\nA priest, [[Gerald Ridsdale]], was jailed in 1994 for 18 years, with a minimum of 15 years, after pleading guilty to 46 counts of child sexual offences, including buggery, indecent assault and gross indecency, committed over two decades on 21 victims.<ref name=\"the-age-good-men-of-the-cloth\">{{cite news | last = Ellingsen | first = Peter | title = Ballarat's good men of the cloth | work = [[The Age]] | date = 14 June 2002 | url = http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2002/06/13/1023864324376.html | accessdate = 19 June 2010 | location=Melbourne}}</ref> In 2006, he pleaded guilty to 35 additional charges relating to [[indecent assault]] against 10 boys.<ref name=\"abc-guilty-plea\">{{cite news |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2006/08/07/1708350.htm |title=Former priest pleads guilty to child abuse |work=[[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]] |date=7 August 2006 |accessdate=25 November 2009 }}</ref> On these charges, he was sentenced to 13 years imprisonment, with a minimum of seven years.<ref name=\"the-age-criticism\">{{cite news | url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/national/victims-slam-pedophile-sentence/2006/08/11/1154803068610.html |accessdate=25 November 2009 |location=Melbourne |work=The Age |first=Jamie |last=Berry |title=Victims slam pedophile sentence |date=11 August 2006}}</ref> A few of his victims criticised the sentence.<ref name=\"the-age-criticism\" /> Ridsdale would have been eligible for parole in August 2013, at the age of 79.<ref name=\"the-age-criticism\" /> On 20 June 2013, Ridsdale was again charged by Victoria Police with an additional 84 offences against 14 victims committed between 1961 and 1981.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2013-05-31/paedophile-priest-gerald-ridsdale-interviewed-by-detectives/4724678 |title=Paedophile priest Gerald Ridsdale interviewed over new abuse claims |work=[[AM (Australian radio series)|AM]], [[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]] |location=Australia |date=31 May 2014 |access-date=22 May 2015 |author=Donovan, Samantha }}</ref> He pleaded guilty to 29 counts (27 of indecent assault, one count of buggery and one count of carnal knowledge of a girl under the age of 16) committed between 1960 and 1980 and asked for a further 27 counts to be taken into consideration at sentencing, which will take place at a date to be fixed.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2013-11-18/paedophile-priest-gerald-ridsdale-pleads-guilty-to-new-child-se/5099280 |title=Paedophile priest Gerald Ridsdale pleads guilty to 29 child sex offences |work=[[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]] |location=Australia |date=18 November 2013 |access-date= |author= }}</ref> After pleading guilty to the above charges, including raping and abusing children as young as four, Ridsdale was sentenced to eight years in prison in April 2014 and will be eligible for parole in April 2019.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-04-08/paedophile-priest-gerald-ridsdale-sentenced/5375506 |title=Paedophile priest Gerald Ridsdale sentenced to 8 years in jail for child abuse |date=18 March 2014 |work=[[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]] |location=Australia |access-date=21 May 2015 }}</ref> The latest charges bring the tally of Ridsdale's confirmed victims to 54.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-03-18/victim-of-paedophile-priest-felt-dirty2c-scared-and-confused2/5328526 |title=Victims of paedophile priest Gerald Ridsdale felt dirty, scared and confused, court told |work=[[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]] |location=Australia |date=18 March 2014 |access-date=21 May 2015 |author= }}</ref> In May 2015 Ridsdale gave an account of his offending in evidence to the Royal Commission on Institutional Responses to Child Sexual Abuse.<ref>J. Franklin, [http://www.maths.unsw.edu.au/~jim/franklinridsdale.pdf Gerald Ridsdale, pedophile priest, in his own words], ''Journal of the Australian Catholic Historical Society'' 36 (2105), 219-230.</ref>\n\nRidsdale pleaded guilty to a further 20 offences against 10 boys and a girl on 13 April 2017. These offences were committed between 1961 and 1988 in western Victoria and are expected to extend his release date further into the future.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-04-13/paedophile-priest-gerald-ridsdale-pleads-guilty/8442132 |title=Gerald Ridsdale, paedophile priest, pleads guilty to more sexual abuse involving 11 children in western Victoria |first=Emma |last=Younger |publisher=[[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]] |date=13 April 2017 |accessdate=13 April 2017}}</ref>  On 15 August 2017 Ridsdale pleaded guilty to 23 charges including two counts of rape and one of buggery, for abusing 12 children, 11 boys and  aged 6 to 13, between 1962 and 1988 in the Victoria state city of Ballarat and the surrounding area.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/australia-court-hears-harrowing-accounts-child-abuse-diocese-linked-vatican-651096|title=Australian court hears harrowing accounts of child abuse by pedophile priest|first=Sofia Lotto Persio On 8/15/17 at 1:54 PM|last=EDT|date=15 August 2017|website=Newsweek}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2017/aug/15/paedophile-priest-gerald-ridsdale-abused-girl-on-church-altar-victorian-court-told|title=Paedophile priest Gerald Ridsdale abused girl on church altar, Victorian court told|first=Australian Associated|last=Press|date=15 August 2017|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 August 2011, [[Congregation of Christian Brothers#Australia|Robert Charles Best]], a [[Congregation of Christian Brothers|Christian Brother]], was sentenced in the Victorian County Court to 14 years and nine months jail, with a non-parole period of 11 years and three months, for 27 offences involving sexual abuse of 11 boys. Best taught at Catholic primary and secondary schools in Ballarat, Box Hill and Geelong (all in Victoria, Australia) between the 1960s and 1980s. Best has been convicted by a jury and has pleaded guilty to more than 40 child sex offences against dozens of students, some as young as eight years old.<ref name=Best>{{cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2011-07-25/christian-brother-found-guilty-of-chiild-sex-offences/2809210 |title=Christian brother found guilty of child sex offences |work=[[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]] |location=Australia |date=25 July 2011 |accessdate=25 July 2011 |author= }}</ref> {{as of|2011}} Best had not been expelled by the Christian Brothers and the order had expended more than {{AUD}}1&nbsp;million on his legal costs.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/breaking-news/pedophile-christian-brother-robert-bests-appeal-an-insult-victims/story-fn3dxity-1226142054531 |title=Pedophile Christian Brother Robert Best's appeal an insult-victims |work=The Australian |date=20 September 2011 |accessdate=31 October 2011 |author=Cresswell, Joel |agency=AAP }}</ref> In May 2013, the Christian Brothers admitted to Victoria's parliamentary inquiry into child abuse they did what they could to defend members accused of sexual assault against children. They admitted to hiring a private investigator to follow one of Best's victims. In addition to paying the aforementioned legal costs, the church also paid hundreds of thousands to defend other members also accused of rape.<ref>{{cite news |author=Morris, Madeleine |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2013-05-03/christian-brothers-spent-1m-defending-paedophile/4668944?section=vic |title=Christian Brothers spent $1m defending paedophile |work=[[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]] |location=Australia |date=3 May 2013 |accessdate=3 May 2013 }}</ref>\n\nOn 21 August 2019, Ballarat Bishop [[Paul Bird (bishop)|Paul Bird]] acknowledged that Pell, who had lost his appeal in the state of Victoria, had ties to this Melbourne suffragan diocese and apologized for the history of sex abuse in the Diocese as well.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.standard.net.au/story/6340694/archbishop-urges-pell-verdict-respect/|title=Archbishop urges Pell verdict respect|first=Kaitlyn Offer and Megan|last=Neil|date=21 August 2019|website=The Standard}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 September 2019, the Diocese of Ballarat released a statement admitting that the high-ranking clergy in the Diocese knew of sex abuse claims against Gerald Ridsdale and afterwards made efforts to shield Ridsdale from prosecution.<ref name=ridsdaleprotection>{{cite web|author=Michael Sainsbury |url=https://cruxnow.com/church-in-oceania/2019/09/13/new-admission-by-diocese-could-cost-australian-church-millions-in-claims/ |title=New admission by diocese could cost Australian Church millions in claims |publisher=Cruxnow.com |date=2019-09-13 |accessdate=2019-09-22}}</ref> This confession came in the wake of civil lawsuit filed against the Diocese by one of Ridsdale's victims.<ref name=ridsdaleprotection />\n\nIn addition to the Archdiocese of Melbourne sex abuse charges, Pell also faces numerous sex abuse charges stemming from his time in the Diocese of Ballarat.<ref name=Pellcharged>{{Cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-06-29/cardinal-george-pell-charged-sexual-assault-offences/8547668|title=George Pell told to face court on historical sexual assault charges|date=2017-06-29|work=ABC News|access-date=2020-04-02|language=en-AU}}</ref> The 3 episode miniseries Revelation, which aired on ABC TV on March 17, March 31 and April 2, 2020,<ref>https://www.abc.net.au/radio/programs/abc-news-specials/episode-3/12114314</ref> revealed two men, identified as Bernie and Peter Clarke, who accused Pell of sexually abusing them as boys when he served at the Catholic-run orphanage where they resided in the 1970s.<ref>https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-04-02/george-pell-ballarat-allegations-revelation/12109952</ref> The new sex abuse allegations against Pell were also investigated by Australian journalist [[Sarah Ferguson (journalist)|Sarah Ferguson]].<ref name=pellorphanage>https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-04-02/george-pell-ballarat-allegations-revelation/12109952</ref> Despite the fact that his sex abuse convictions related to his time in the Archdiocese of Melbourne were later overturned, Pell still faces 10 civil lawsuits, with some stemming from his time in the Diocese of Ballarat<ref>https://cruxnow.com/vatican/2020/04/vatican-welcomes-pell-verdict-affirms-anti-abuse-resolve-as-survivors-protest/</ref><ref>https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2019/mar/04/george-pell-to-be-sued-over-alleged-1970s-sexual-abuse-in-ballarat</ref>\n\n===Marist Brothers===\nIn September 2018, Marist Brother Gerard McNamara, 80, was sentenced to nine months in prison for molested five boys who were aspiring athletes at St Paul's Catholic College, where served as principal, in Traralgon between 1970 and 1975.<ref name=maristbrotherconviction /> He also molested one of these boy 30 times.<ref name=maristbrotherconviction>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2018/sep/03/marist-brother-who-sexually-assaulted-five-boys-sentenced-to-nine-months-jail|title=Marist brother who sexually assaulted five boys sentenced to nine months' jail|first=Australian Associated|last=Press|date=3 September 2018|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref> In June 2019, the [[Marist Brothers]] produced a list of 154 members who were accused of sexually abusing children in Australia between 1980 and 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-au/news/australia/the-marist-brothers-and-a-secret-list-of-154-accused-child-sex-offenders/ar-AADmvjB|title=The Marist Brothers and a secret list of 154 accused child sex offenders|website=www.msn.com}}</ref>\n\n===Archdiocese of Brisbane===\nIn June 2010, Brisbane priest Michael Ambrose Endicott plead guilty to take indecent photos of two schoolboys between 1977 and 1978 and received a one-year suspended prison sentence.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://brokenrites.org.au/archives/nletter/page233-michael-ambrose-endicott.html|title=Full story: Father Michael Ambrose Endicott sentenced|website=brokenrites.org.au}}</ref> In March 2019, he received an 18-month prison sentence after being convicted of making boys strip nude for photos during the 1970s and 1980s,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.blayneychronicle.com.au/story/5943329/qld-priest-guilty-of-historical-sex-abuse/|title=Qld priest guilty of historical sex abuse|date=8 March 2019|website=Blayney Chronicle}}</ref> only to have this conviction overturned the next month.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-04-17/catholic-priest-acquitted-of-indecent-dealing-child-charges/11024008|title=Former priest's indecent dealing conviction overturned on appeal|date=17 April 2019|website=ABC News}}</ref>\n\n====Diocese of Townsville====\n{{see also|Roman Catholic Diocese of Townsville}}\nNotable cases include: Neville Joseph Creen - molested young girls while he served as a priest at Mount Isa, north-west Queensland, from 1973 to 1981. In Brisbane District Court on 12 September 2003, Creen (aged 63) was sentenced to three-and-half years' jail with a 14-month minimum after admitting to 34 indecent dealing charges involving 18 girls under the age of 13. One girl was aged just 5 when Creen abused her at a youth camp and later at the home of her grandparents. Creen pleaded guilty to a further six charges on 4 November 2004 and was sentenced to an additional two years jail.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://cathnews.acu.edu.au/309/83.php |work=CathNews |title=Prison for Townsville Diocese priest who molested 18 girls |date=15 September 2003 |accessdate=18 September 2011 }}</ref>\n\n===Archdiocese of Perth===\n{{see also|Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Perth}}\nIn 1995, Gerard William Dick, a self-confessed sexually abusive priest, was sentenced to three and a half years jail for 10 incidents of indecently dealing with boys aged between 8 and 10 at a [[Congregation of Christian Brothers|Christian Brothers]]' orphanage in [[Western Australia]].<ref>{{cite book |first=Bruce |last=Blyth |title=In the Shadow of the Cross: the story of VOICES : how the Christian Brothers' victims fought for justice |publisher=P&B Press |location=Perth, Western Australia |year=1997 |page=106 |isbn=0-646-33774-2 |type=paperback}}</ref>\n\nDavid Christian was fined {{AUD}}10,500 on seven charges of indecently assaulting boys at the Marist Brothers school.<ref>{{cite book |last=Blyth |title=In the Shadow of the Cross: the story of VOICES : how the Christian Brothers' victims fought for justice |page=181 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1994, the [[Parliament of Western Australia]] was presented a petition with 30,000 signatures which demanded an inquiry into the sexual and physical assault that took place in various institutions run by the [[Congregation of Christian Brothers|Christian Brothers]] including [[Castledare Boys' Home]], [[Bindoon, Western Australia|Bindoon]], [[Clontarf Aboriginal College|Clontarf]] and [[Tardun, Western Australia|Tardun]].<ref name=\"lateline sins\">{{cite interview |subject=McDonald, Alex |subject2=Wilkins, John |subject3=Ransom, David |display-authors=etal |interviewer=[[Maxine McKew]] |title=Sins Of The Brothers |type=Interview |url=http://www.abc.net.au/lateline/stories/s17579.htm |format=transcript |work=[[Lateline]] |publisher=[[ABC (Australian TV channel)|ABC TV]] |location=Australia |date=24 November 1998 |access-date=15 May 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080420190410/http://www.abc.net.au/lateline/stories/s17579.htm |archive-date=20 April 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"murray speech\"/>\n\nThe Christian Brothers accepted that there was strong evidence that many of the allegations were true, and made a public apology.<ref name=\"lateline sins\" /> A legal action brought by over 200 former students ran from 1993 in the [[New South Wales Supreme Court]] and was finalised in 1996 with an out of court settlement.<ref name=\"murray speech\">{{cite speech |title=Key note address |author=Murray, Andrew |author-link=Andrew Murray (Australian politician) |date=28 October 2002 |event=1st International Congress on Child Migration |publisher=[[Australian Democrats]] |url=http://www.andrewmurray.org.au/Media/Speech_Display.htm?speech_id=1035&display=1 |access-date=15 May 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090912024052/http://andrewmurray.org.au/Media/Speech_Display.htm?speech_id=1035&display=1 |archivedate=12 September 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, retired Subiaco and Shenton Park priest Patrick Holmes was sentenced to three years jail. He had pled guilty to six child-sex charges dating between 1969 and 1981. He later appeared in court in 2018 and again in 2019, entering a not-guilty plea in response to 16 new charges filed after an investigation by the WA Police's Child Abuse Squad.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brokenrites.org.au/drupal/node/301 |access-date=31 March 2020 |title= This priest has been in jail, and now he faces new charges}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2019, retired Perth priest Allan John Mithen received a 13-month suspended prison sentence after pleading guilty to two counts of sexually abusing an Aborigine girl at a mission in 1965.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sbs.com.au/nitv/nitv-news/article/2019/01/16/its-disgusting-community-anger-former-priest-receives-suspended-sentence|title=\u2018It\u2019s disgusting\u2019: Community anger as former priest receives suspended sentence|website=NITV}}</ref> In March 2019, Joseph Tran, a well known and popular Perth priest, committed suicide after accusations surfaced that he had molested a girl for years.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thenewdaily.com.au/news/state/wa/2019/03/23/wa-priest-accused-of-molesting-teen-girl-found-dead/|title=WA priest accused of molesting teen girl found dead &#124; The New Daily WA priest accused of molesting teen girl found dead|date=23 March 2019|website=The New Daily}}</ref>\n\n====Diocese of Bunbury====\n{{see also|Roman Catholic Diocese of Bunbury}}\nAdrian Richard Van Klooster - pleaded guilty to four counts of indecently dealing with children under the age of 13 and was found with child pornography on his computer.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.catholicweekly.com.au/03/feb/2/15.html |title=Bishop's plea after priest convicted |date=2 February 2003 |accessdate=18 September 2011 |work=The Catholic Weekly |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927065636/http://www.catholicweekly.com.au/03/feb/2/15.html# |archive-date=27 September 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Archdiocese of Hobart===\n\n====Marist Fathers of Tasmania====\n{{see also|Marist Regional College}}\nNotable cases include: in 2007 Gregory Ferguson was sentenced to two years jail (eligible for parole after 12 months) for offences in 1971 against two boys aged 13 at Marist College, Burnie, Tasmania. On 13 December 2007 he was sentenced to an additional three years jail for offences against a third boy.;<ref>{{cite news|title=Pedophile may get parole after one year's prison |url=http://cathnews.acu.edu.au/705/101.php|accessdate=19 January 2011|newspaper=CathNews|date=17 May 2007}}</ref> in 2008 a jury found former priest Roger Michael Bellemore guilty on three counts of maintaining a sexual relationship with a young person under the age of 17 years in the 1960s and 1970s while he was at the same college.<ref>{{cite news |title=Guilty verdict for former priest |work=ABC News |location=Australia |date=12 February 2008 |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2008-02-12/guilty-verdict-for-former-priest/1040112 |accessdate=22 September 2011}}</ref> By December 2018, six former priests who taught at the College had been convicted of committing acts of sexual abuse.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2018/dec/20/former-priest-becomes-sixth-teacher-at-burnie-marist-college-convicted-of-historic-child-sex-offences|title=Former priest becomes sixth teacher at Burnie Marist College convicted of historic child sex offences|first=Calla|last=Wahlquist|date=21 December 2018|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref>\n\n===Archdiocese of Canberra and Goulburn===\n{{Main|Sexual abuse scandal in Canberra and Goulburn archdiocese}}\nIn February 2008, a teacher at Marist College Canberra, Brother John William Chute (also known as Brother Kostka) pleaded guilty in the ACT Magistrates Court to 11 charges of indecently assaulting students of the college during the 1980s.<ref>{{cite news |title=Marist Brother pleads guilty to assaulting boys |work=ABC News |location=Australia |date=21 February 2008 |accessdate=18 September 2011 |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2008/02/21/2168728.htm?section=justin }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.canberratimes.com.au/news/local/news/general/two-years-in-jail-for-brother-kostka/795061.aspx |title=Two years in jail for Brother Kostka |work=The Canberra Times |date=23 June 2008 |accessdate=18 September 2011 |first=Victor |last=Violante }}{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Damages for sexual abuse have also been sought by former students at [[Marist College Canberra]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2008/02/25/2171625.htm |title=More teachers linked to Marist sex abuse case |work=ABC News |location=Australia |date=25 February 2008 |accessdate=18 September 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cathnews.com/article.aspx?aeid=7794 |title=Marists apologise for Canberra abuse |date=24 June 2008 |accessdate=18 September 2011 |work=CathNews |location=Australia |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927121400/http://www.cathnews.com/article.aspx?aeid=7794 |archivedate=27 September 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.canberratimes.com.au/news/local/news/general/schools-paedophile-ring/1565239.aspx |title=School's 'paedophile ring' |work=The Canberra Times |date=11 July 2009 |accessdate=18 September 2011 |first=Victor |last=Violante |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927233708/http://www.canberratimes.com.au/news/local/news/general/schools-paedophile-ring/1565239.aspx# |archive-date=27 September 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> A teacher at [[Daramalan College]] in Canberra was also charged with numerous sexual assaults in 2000; however he committed suicide shortly after he was charged.<ref>{{cite news |work=ABC Canberra |title=Colleges settle sex abuse cases |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2009/12/01/2758197.htm?site=canberra |date=1 December 2009 |accessdate=1 January 2009}}</ref> Seven further charges against Chute relating to alleged offences committed before 1985 were dropped, due to a legal limitation that charges relating to sexual indecency had to be made within a year. In June 2008, Chute was sentenced in the [[Supreme Court of the Australian Capital Territory|ACT Supreme Court]] to six years in jail, serving two years in prison, one year in weekend detention, and three years suspended.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-03-28/canberra-brother-kostka-marist-sex-offences-court/10948376|title=Court accepts notorious paedophile abused boys, but can't convict him|first=Elizabeth|last=Byrne|date=28 March 2019|website=ABC News}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Two years in jail for Brother Kostka |work=The Canberra Times |date=23 June 2008 |url=http://www.canberratimes.com.au/news/local/news/general/two-years-in-jail-for-brother-kostka/795061.aspx |author=Violante, Victor |accessdate=6 September 2019 }}{{dead link|date=May 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Pope Benedict's statement==\n{{Main|Ecclesiastical response to Catholic sex abuse cases}}\nOn 19 July 2008, before a [[wikt:congregation|congregation]] of 3,400 assembled in Sydney's [[St Mary's Cathedral, Sydney|St Mary's Cathedral]], [[Pope Benedict XVI]] lamented that [[child sex abuse]] had taken place and the pain it caused. He also condemned those responsible for it and demanded punishment for them.  However, he did not state or imply that the institutional church, or any of its leaders, accepted any responsibility for what had taken place. His statement reads:<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-pope-australia-abuse-text-idUSL1868657420080719|title=Text of Pope's apology for sexual abuse in Australia|date=2008-07-19|work=Reuters|access-date=2019-11-29|language=en}}</ref>\n<blockquote>\n\"Here I would like to pause to acknowledge the shame which we have all felt as a result of the sexual abuse of minors by some clergy and religious in this country. I am deeply sorry for the pain and suffering the victims have endured and I assure them that, as their pastor, I too share in their suffering. ... Victims should receive compassion and care, and those responsible for these evils must be brought to justice. These misdeeds, which constitute so grave a betrayal of trust, deserve unequivocal condemnation. I ask all of you to support and assist your bishops, and to work together with them in combating this evil. It is an urgent priority to promote a safer and more wholesome environment, especially for young people.\"\n</blockquote>\n\nOn 21 July 2008, before flying out of Australia, Pope Benedict met at St Mary's Cathedral, Sydney, with two male and two female victims of sex abuse by priests. He listened to their stories and celebrated Mass with them.<ref>{{cite news |work=[[The Australian]] |year=2008 |accessdate=21 July 2008 |url=http://www.theaustralian.news.com.au/story/0,25197,24049778-601,00.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080727154145/http://www.theaustralian.news.com.au/story/0%2C25197%2C24049778-601%2C00.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=27 July 2008 |title=Pope Benedict meets abuse victims before flying out |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The [[Premier of New South Wales]], [[Morris Iemma]], said that \"Hopefully it will be a sign of righting the wrongs of the past and of a better future and better treatment by the church of the victims and their families.\"<ref Name=inquirer>{{cite news |url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/breakingnews/world/view/20080719-149455/Popes-Australia-sex-abuse-apology-not-enough----critics |work=Inquirer.net |title=Pope's Australia sex abuse apology not enough -- critics |date=19 July 2008 |location=Philippines |agency=[[Agence France-Presse]] |accessdate=18 September 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120729220022/http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/breakingnews/world/view/20080719-149455/Popes-Australia-sex-abuse-apology-not-enough----critics# |archive-date=29 July 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2008/jul/20/catholicism.australia |location=United Kingdom | work=The Observer | first=Barbara | last=McMahon | title=Pope says he is 'deeply sorry' to Australian sexual abuse victims | date=20 July 2008 |accessdate=18 September 2011}}</ref>\n\nMark Fabbro, a victim of abuse and member of the Catholic Abuse Survivors Collective, said that while he was \"happy to receive the apology, we still consider it indirect and insufficient\".{{Citation needed|date=November 2019}} Chris MacIsaac of the victims' rights advocacy group [[Broken Rites]] said the Pope had taken his apology further than his previous comments on the issue as he has \"never put it quite so strongly before\", but expressed disappointment that the Pope had not made his apology directly to sexual abuse victims.{{Citation needed|date=November 2019}} One Australian victim of sexual abuse by a Catholic priest has stated in the media: \"Dealing with the church itself was a hell of a lot more traumatic than dealing with the abuse''.\"''<ref>{{cite news |first1=Nick |last1=McKenzie |first2=Rafael |last2=Epstein |title=Priests kept working despite investigations |work=Sydney Morning Herald |date=17 May 2010 |url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/priests-kept-working-despite-investigations-20100516-v6f5.html |accessdate=16 May 2010 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Royal Commission into Institutional Responses to Child Sexual Abuse]]\n* [[Roman Catholicism in Australia]]\n* [[William Kamm]] - leader of a schismatic group whose sexual offences predate his schism from the church\n* [[Broken Rites|Broken Rites Australia]] - support and advocacy group for church-related sex abuse victims in Australia\n* [[Catholic sexual abuse cases in New Zealand]]\n* [[Roman Catholic sex abuse cases by country]]\n\n'''General:'''\n*[[Abuse]]\n*[[Child abuse]]\n*[[Child sexual abuse]]\n*[[Religious abuse]]\n*[[Sexual abuse]]\n*[[Sexual misconduct]]\n*[[Spiritual abuse]]\n\n==External links==\n* [https://australiancatholichistoricalsociety.com.au/history-resources/the-sexual-abuse-crisis/ Australian Catholic Historical Society: The Sexual Abuse Crisis]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{SACC}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2011}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Australia}}\n[[Category:Catholic Church sexual abuse scandals in Australia| ]]\n[[Category:Child abuse in Australia]]\n[[Category:Rape in Australia]]\n", "text_old": "{{see also|Catholic Church sexual abuse cases}}\n{{short description|Catholic Church sexual abuse cases in Australia}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=November 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n'''Catholic sexual abuse cases in Australia''', like [[Catholic sexual abuse scandal]]s elsewhere, have involved convictions, trials and ongoing investigations into allegations of [[sex crimes]] committed by [[Catholic priest]]s,  members of [[Abuse by members of Roman Catholic orders|religious orders]] and other personnel which have come to light in recent decades, along with the growing awareness of sexual abuse within other religious and secular institutions.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/vaticancityandholysee/7429933/Child-abuse-scandals-faced-by-Roman-Catholic-Church.html |title=Child abuse scandals faced by Roman Catholic Church |date=12 March 2010 |work=The Telegraph |location=United Kingdom |accessdate=21 September 2011}}</ref> Criticisms of the Church have centred both on the nature and extent of abuse, and on historical and contemporary management of allegations by Church officials. Internally, the Church began updating its protocols in the 1990s, and papal apologies for abuse in Australia were made by [[Pope John Paul II]] and [[Pope Benedict XVI]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vatican.va/holy_father/john_paul_ii/apost_exhortations/documents/hf_jp-ii_exh_20011122_ecclesia-in-oceania_en.html |author=Pope John Paul II |work=Apostolic exhortation |publisher=Libreria Editrice Vaticana |title=Ecclesia in Oceania |location=Rome |date=22 November 2001 |accessdate=30 March 2012 }}</ref> A number of government enquiries have also examined church practices - most notably the 2015-17 [[Royal Commission into Institutional Responses to Child Sexual Abuse]]. The Royal Commission established that some 4,444 claimants alleged incidents of child sexual abuse in 4,756 reported claims to Catholic Church authorities (some claimants made a claim of child sexual abuse against more than one Catholic Church authority) and at least 1,880 suspected abusers from 1980 to 2015. Most of those suspected of abuse were Catholic priests and religious brothers and 62 percent of the survivors who told the commission they were abused in religious institutions were abused in a Catholic facility.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/12/14/world/australia/australia-sexual-abuse-children.html|title=Australia and Catholic Church \u2018Failed\u2019 Abused Children, Inquiry Finds|author=Williams, Jecqueline|date=14 December 2017|newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref><ref name=\"childabuseroyalcommission.gov.au\">[http://childabuseroyalcommission.gov.au/getattachment/e352891e-2cb8-4abf-96b9-4449296c470b/Analysis-of-claims-of-child-sexual-abuse-made-with Royal Commission: ANALYSIS OF CLAIMS OF CHILD SEXUAL ABUSE MADE WITH RESPECT TO CATHOLIC CHURCH INSTITUTIONS IN AUSTRALIA] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170731111106/http://childabuseroyalcommission.gov.au/getattachment/e352891e-2cb8-4abf-96b9-4449296c470b/Analysis-of-claims-of-child-sexual-abuse-made-with |date=31 July 2017 }}; June 2017</ref>\n\nAustralia's Catholic leaders had been among the first in the world to publicly address management of child abuse: In 1996, the church issued a document, ''Towards Healing'', which it described as seeking to \"establish a compassionate and just system for dealing with complaints of abuse\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.adelaide.catholic.org.au/sites/ProfessionalStandards/dealing-with-complaints-of-abuse/towards-healing |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722062507/http://www.adelaide.catholic.org.au/sites/ProfessionalStandards/dealing-with-complaints-of-abuse/towards-healing |archivedate=22 July 2011 |title=Towards Healing |work=Professional Standards Office |publisher=Australian Catholic Bishops Conference |year=1996 |accessdate=30 March 2012 }}</ref> Inquiries have since established that historically, Church officials had often failed to prevent future abuse by clergy who had come to their attention by [[Parish transfers of abusive priests|transferring clergy]] and religious to new parishes or dioceses, and not stripping them of their religious status.<ref>{{cite news |first=James |last=Campbell |title=Church must face scrutiny for child sex abuse |work=Sunday Herald Sun |date=29 August 2010 |url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/opinion/church-must-face-scrutiny-for-child-sex-abuse/story-fn5sqiu3-1225911324431 |accessdate=24 September 2011 |location=Australia }}</ref> A widely reported 2012 claim in a Victorian police report that 43 suicide deaths were directly related to abuse by clergy spurred the formation of a Victorian state Parliamentary  inquiry into the Handling of Child Abuse by Religious and other Organisations.<ref>[http://www.theaustralian.com.au/national-affairs/in-depth/royal-commission/victoria-police-in-false-claim-on-childabuse-suicides/news-story/ac8da079994e08ab94eec0c951f0b1e9 Victoria Police in false claim on child-abuse suicides]; theaustralian.com.au; 25 July</ref><ref>{{cite news |author1=McKenzie, Nick |author2=Baker, Richard |author3=Lee, Jane |title=Church's suicide victims |work=Canberra Times |date=13 April 2012 |url=http://www.canberratimes.com.au/victoria/churchs-suicide-victims-20120412-1wwox.html |accessdate=2 July 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120613181306/http://www.canberratimes.com.au/victoria/churchs-suicide-victims-20120412-1wwox.html |archive-date=13 June 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In October 2012, the Chief Commissioner of Victoria Police, [[Ken Lay (police officer)|Ken Lay]], in a submission to a parliamentary inquiry on the issue, recommended that some of the church's actions to hinder investigations (including dissuading victims from reporting to police, failing to engage with police and alerting suspects of allegations against them) be criminalised.<ref>{{cite news |author1=Lee, Jane |author2=Zwartz, Barney |title=Police slam Catholic Church |work=The Age |location=Australia |date=11 October 2012 |accessdate= |url=http://www.theage.com.au/victoria/police-slam-catholic-church-20121010-27dr2.html }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Gillard Government]] called a wide-ranging Royal Commission in 2013 to examine religious and non-religious institutions and their responses to child abuse allegations. [[Denis Hart|Archbishop Hart]], president of the [[Australian Catholic Bishops Conference]], said he welcomed the [[Royal Commission]], as did the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Sydney|Archbishop of Sydney]], Cardinal [[George Pell]] who said he hoped it would help victims and stop a \"smear campaign\" against the Church.<ref>{{cite news |title=Abuse inquiry to run 'as long as it takes' |work=The Australian |date=13 November 2012 |url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/breaking-news/catholic-archbishop-welcomes-inquiry/story-fn3dxiwe-1226515563793 |accessdate=13 November 2012 |author=Drape, Julian |agency=AAP }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title = Cardinal Welcomes Royal Commission | work = Catholic Communications, Sydney Archdiocese | date = 16 November 2012 | url = http://www.sydneycatholic.org/news/latest_news/2012/20121115_453.shtml | accessdate = 20 November 2012 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20121118040644/http://www.sydneycatholic.org/news/latest_news/2012/20121115_453.shtml | archive-date = 18 November 2012 | url-status = dead | df = dmy-all }}</ref> Pell was himself later convicted of child sex offences, but was acquitted by the [[High Court of Australia]] on 7 April 2020.<ref name=\"CNA_Pell\">{{cite web |title=Reports of Pell guilty verdict emerge, despite gag order |url=https://www.catholicnewsagency.com/news/reports-of-pell-guilty-verdict-emerge-despite-gag-order-32220 |website=Catholic News Agency |publisher=Catholic News Agency |accessdate=31 May 2019}}</ref>  The Bishops Conference, established a national co-ordinating body, called the [[Truth, Justice and Healing Council]] to oversee the church's engagement with the Royal Commission and the pastoral and other ramifications that arose from the sexual abuse scandal.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://www.catholic.org.au/acbc-media/media-centre/media-releases-new/1335-announcement-of-chair-and-ceo-of-royal-commission-council-1 |title=Announcement of Chair and CEO of the Catholic Church Council for the Royal Commission|date=12 December 2012|publisher=[[Australian Catholic Bishops Conference]]|accessdate=16 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nOf the 201 Catholic Church authorities surveyed by the Royal Commission, 92 (46%) reported having received at least one claim of child sexual abuse. Overall, some 4,444 claimants alleged incidents of abuse in 4,756 reported claims over the period 1950-2015 (86% of claims related to pre-1990 incidents). The 3,057 claims resulting in a payment for redress amounted to $268 million between 1980 and 2015. Alleged perpetrators were overwhelmingly male (90%) and religious brothers were disproportionally highly responsible (having the most claimants and some 37% of all alleged perpetrators, despite being numerically inferior to priests and religious sisters).  By means of a weighted index, the Commission found that at 75 archdioceses/dioceses and religious institutes with priest members examined, some 7 per cent of priests (who worked in Australia between 1950 and 2009<ref name=\"singledOut\">{{cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2017/12/15/571013476/catholic-church-singled-out-in-australian-sex-abuse-report |title=Catholic Church Singled Out In Australian Sex Abuse Report|author=Neuman, Scott|date=15 December 2017| accessdate = 15 December 2017}}</ref>) were alleged perpetrators (this finding did not represent allegations tested in a court of law).<ref name=\"childabuseroyalcommission.gov.au\"/>  Senior Counsel Gail Furness told the Commission that \"Children were ignored or worse, punished. Allegations were not investigated. Priests and religious leaders were moved. The parishes or communities to which they were moved knew nothing of their past. Documents were not kept or they were destroyed.\"<ref name=aljazzeraabuse>{{cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/02/scale-catholic-church-sex-crimes-revealed-170206135244774.html|title='Shocking' scale of Catholic Church sex crimes revealed|website=www.aljazeera.com}}</ref><ref name=royalabuse>{{cite web|url=https://www.childabuseroyalcommission.gov.au/case-studies/case-study-50-institutional-review-catholic-church-authorities|title=Case Study 50: Institutional review of Catholic Church authorities|date=6 February 2017|website=Royal Commission into Institutional Responses to Child Sexual Abuse}}</ref>  By August 2011, according to [[Broken Rites]], a support and advocacy group for church-related sex abuse victims, there had been over 100 cases in Australia where Catholic priests had been charged for sex offences against minors, as well as others involving non-custodial sentences and inconclusive proceedings.<ref>{{cite web |work=Broken Rites |title=Black Collar Crime in Australia |url=http://brokenrites.alphalink.com.au/nletter/bccrime.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010422203616/http://brokenrites.alphalink.com.au/nletter/bccrime.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=22 April 2001 |date=28 August 2011 |accessdate=18 September 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn 3 June 2019, 18 months after being ordered to do so by the country's Royal Commission into Institutional Child Sexual Abuse, the Australian Catholic Church published its National Catholic Safeguarding Standards.<ref name=ncrstandards>{{cite web|url=https://www.ncronline.org/news/quick-reads/australian-catholic-church-releases-standards-child-protection|title=Australian Catholic Church releases standards for child protection|date=3 June 2019|website=National Catholic Reporter}}</ref> The standards closely parallel the commission's recommendations as well as norms enshrined by the government in the National Principles for Child Safe Organizations, although some provisions were watered down.<ref name=ncrstandards /> One notable alteration concerned the number of hours per year that people should be undergoing professional and pastoral supervision, which was reduced from the recommended 12 hours to six hours.<ref name=ncrstandards />\n\n==Cases==\n\n===Archdiocese of Adelaide===\n{{see also|Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Adelaide}}\nOn 13 September 2011, [[Australian Senate|Senator]] [[Nick Xenophon]] used parliamentary privilege to name an Adelaide priest as the alleged perpetrator of six sexual assaults on [[John Hepworth]] about 50 years earlier. Senator Xenophon alleged that the Vicar-General of Adelaide, Monsignor [[David Cappo]], had been provided with detailed allegations in 2008 but had failed to act upon them, the investigations still being \"at a preliminary stage\" and the priest concerned not being stood down during the investigation.<ref>{{cite news |first=Mark |last=Metherell |title=Senator names priest on 'rape' |work=The Sydney Morning Herald |date=14 September 2011 |url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/senator-names-priest-on-rape-20110913-1k82k.html |accessdate=14 September 2011 }}</ref> Monsignor Cappo subsequently resigned from several governmental positions.<ref>{{cite news | title = David Cappo resigns over John Hepworth case | date = 15 September 2011 | work = news.com.au | url = http://www.news.com.au/breaking-news/sacappo-resigns-over-hepworth-case/story-e6frfku0-1226138126452 | accessdate = 21 February 2012 }}</ref> The Catholic church established a formal independent inquiry, conducted by Michael Abbott,  {{post-nominals|country=AUS|QC}}, found that there was no substance to the allegations.<ref>{{cite news | title = No substance to priest John Hepworth's rape claim - church | date = 28 November 2011 | work = news.com.au | url = http://www.news.com.au/breaking-news/no-substance-to-priest-john-hepworths-rape-claim-church/story-e6frfku0-1226208362977 | accessdate = 21 February 2012 }}</ref>\n\nFather Albert Davis (d. 2007), a member of the Dominican Fathers, was charged in 2006 with 17 incidents of indecent assault involving seven boys at [[Blackfriars Priory School]] between 1956 and 1960. Davis was committed to stand trial in the Adelaide District Court, but he died before proceedings were commenced.<ref>{{cite news | title = Tasmanian priest guilty of abuse, SA accused dies |  work = Catholic News | date = 27 March 2007 | url = http://cathnews.acu.edu.au/703/165.php | accessdate = 19 September 2011 }}</ref>\n\nFather Charles Barnett pleaded guilty in 2009 (after extradition from Indonesia) to three child sex charges for events between 1977 and 1985 at Crystal Brook and Port Pirie.<ref>{{cite news |title=Extradited ex-priest admits child sex |work=ABC News |location=Australia |date=9 September 2009 |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2009-09-08/extradited-ex-priest-admits-child-sex/1421448?section=justin |accessdate=20 September 2011 }}</ref>\n\n===Archdiocese of Sydney===\n{{see also|Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Sydney}}\nIn 2007, Ross Murrin, 52, a former Sydney Catholic school teacher and [[Marist Brothers|Marist brother]], accused of indecently assaulting eight male Year 5 students at a Daceyville school in south-east Sydney in 1974, pleaded guilty to some of the 21 charges.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2007/09/18/2036400.htm |title=Catholic brother to plead guilty to abuse |work=ABC News |location=Australia |date=18 September 2007 |accessdate=18 September 2011 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Fr. Roger Flaherty received a sentence of two years and two weeks in prison five months after pleading guilty to molesting three altar boys in the 1970s and 1980s.<ref name=flahertygone>{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/nsw/paedophile-catholic-priest-aged-72-sentenced-to-two-years-in-prison-20160225-gn3bq7.html|title=Paedophile Catholic priest aged 72 sentenced to two years in prison|first=Tim|last=Barlass|date=25 February 2016|website=The Sydney Morning Herald}}</ref> However, Flaherty's advanced age and poor health allowed him to be eligible for parole six months into his sentence.<ref name=flahertygone /> Former Sydney Archbishop Cardinal [[James Darcy Freeman|James Freeman]] and Auxiliary Bishop Edward Kelly were accused of shielding Flaherty from prosecution when the acts of sex abuse were committed.<ref name=flahertygone />\n\nIn 2017, Fr. Denis Chrysostom Alexander was arrested in Sydney and faces an extradition to [[Scotland]] for sexual and physical abuse he reportedly committed at the former [[Fort Augustus Abbey]] in the 1970s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-01-24/alleged-abusive-priest-arrested-in-sydney/8208706|title=Australian Catholic priest accused of abuse at Scottish school arrested in Sydney|first=Thomas|last=Oriti|date=24 January 2017|website=ABC News}}</ref> The sex abuse investigation against Alexander also resulted in the Archdiocese of Sydney stripping him being of his priestly faculties in Australia by 2013 as well.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-23477335|title=Abuse claims at ex-boarding school|first=Mark|last=Daly|date=29 July 2013|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-highlands-islands-47949648|title=Abuse claim monk 'should return to Scotland'|first=Mark|last=Daly|date=16 April 2019|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2019, Fr. Anthony Caruana was arrested and charged with sexually abusing five minors, including one male minor, between the years 1982 and 1988 when he was a dormitory manager, rugby coach and band teacher at [[Chevalier College]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/nsw/catholic-priest-charged-over-alleged-child-sex-abuse-at-nsw-school-20190413-p51dt3.html|title=Catholic priest charged over alleged child sex abuse at NSW school|first=Megan Gorrey, Sally|last=Rawsthorne|date=13 April 2019|website=The Sydney Morning Herald}}</ref>\n\n====Diocese of Armidale====\n{{see also|Roman Catholic Diocese of Armidale}}\nThis diocese incorporates 25 parishes and 24 schools within about 90,000&nbsp;km\u00b2<ref>{{cite|url=http://armidale.catholic.org.au/|title=Catholic Diocese of Armidale|work=Catholic Church |location=Australia |date=17 May 2017 |accessdate=17 May 2017 }}</ref> and is clearly, one of, if not the highest density locations of Catholic Child Sexual Abuse in Australia on a per capita basis.  The extraordinary and shocking story of 'Father F', later to be identified as former Armidale local, and former Catholic Priest John Joseph Farrell, was central to the [[ABC Television]] program [[Four Corners (Australian TV program)|Four Corners]] expose \"Unholy Silence\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EI7kMkFEn0g|title=Unholy Silence - Paedophiles in the Catholic Church|via=www.youtube.com}}</ref>  This was first broadcast on Monday 2 July 2012<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/4corners/unholy-silence/4112724|title=Unholy Silence|date=28 June 2012|via=www.abc.net.au}}</ref> and was potentially the final trigger that led to then Prime Minister [[Julia Gillard]] announcing the Royal Commission into Institutional Responses to Child Sexual Abuse.  The reaction of Armidale locals to the program was strong and one of indignation that something should have been done sooner by the Catholic Church.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z_lFsmmPidM|title=Armidale reacts to church abuse investigation|via=www.youtube.com}}</ref> Case Study 44 of the Royal Commission (Held Monday 19 to Thursday 22 September 2016<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.childabuseroyalcommission.gov.au/case-studies/case-study-44-catholic-church-authorities-armidale-and-parramatta|title=Case Study 44: Catholic Church authorities in Armidale and Parramatta|date=12 September 2016|website=Royal Commission into Institutional Responses to Child Sexual Abuse}}</ref>) focused specifically on this case of a former Catholic Priest abusing children over a 20-year period and the alleged cover-up by the Church hierarchy including Father Bernard Flood, Father Richard Gleeson, Monsignor Wayne Peters (Dec), Father Brian Lucas, Monsignor John Usher, Bishop Gerard Hanna (Ret), Bishop Bede Heather (Ret), Bishop Luc Matthys, (most of whom gave evidence to the Royal Commission<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.childabuseroyalcommission.gov.au/sites/default/files/file-list/Case%20Study%2044%20-%20Witness%20list%20-%20Catholic%20Church%20authorities%20in%20Armidale%20and%20Parramatta%20-%20Sydney.pdf?guid=c42216fb-893c-4a72-bb41-2d809b50f86a&type=witnesslistpdf&filename=case-study-44%2C-september-2016%2C-sydney-witness-list&fileextension=pdf |title=CASE STUDY 44: JOHN JOSEPH FARRELL |date=13 September 2016 |website=www.childabuseroyalcommission.gov.au |format=PDF |access-date=2019-09-22}}</ref>), and even Australia's most senior Catholic Cardinal George Pell.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/nsw/royal-commission-monsignor-john-usher-denies-protecting-cardinal-george-pell-20160922-grlrmk.html|title=Royal commission: Monsignor John Usher denies protecting Cardinal George Pell|first=Rachel|last=Browne|date=22 September 2016|website=The Sydney Morning Herald}}</ref>\n\nOn November 1, 2019, former Diocese of Armidale priest David Perrett plead not guilty to 139 charges of child sexual assault at a number of locations, including Armidale, Guyra, Walgett, Moree, Penrith, Bundarra, Lower Creek, and Sawtell between the 1960s and 1990s.<ref>https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-11-01/former-priest-pleads-not-guilty-to-sex-charges/11664202</ref> Perrett, aged 82, had been arrested for these charges and was denied bail in August 2018,<ref>https://www.northerndailyleader.com.au/story/5601642/81yo-retired-priest-refused-bail-on-historical-sex-abuse-charges/</ref> but was later granted bail in April 2019 after he was told he had only six months to a year to live.<ref>https://www.smh.com.au/national/nsw/a-spent-volcano-old-ill-former-priest-bailed-on-131-charges-20190409-p51cip.html</ref>\n\n====Diocese of Maitland-Newcastle====\n{{see also|Roman Catholic Diocese of Maitland-Newcastle|Philip Wilson (bishop)#Allegations of mishandling the reported sexual abuse of children{{!}}Philip Wilson}}\nThe diocese has been referred to as the \"epicentre of Catholic clerical sexual abuse in Australia\"<ref name=Crittenden>{{cite news |first1=Stephen |last1=Crittenden |first2=Suzanne |last2=Smith |title=Archbishop's handling of abuse claims challenged |work=ABC News |location=Australia |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2010/05/17/2901859.htm |date=18 May 2010 |accessdate=16 September 2011}}</ref> due to a number of paedophile priests with extensive abuse records being jailed since 1997, a dedicated clergy abuse police strikeforce (Strike Force Lantle) having laid more than 170 abuse charges.<ref name=\"abc.net.au\">{{cite news |title=Newcastle Catholic Bishop supports abuse inquiry |work=ABC News |location=Australia |date=26 July 2012 |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2012-07-26/newcastle-catholic-bishop-supports-abuse-inquiry/4157078 |accessdate=28 July 2012 }}</ref> Convicted abusers include Father Vincent Ryan (a $6&nbsp;million compensation payout to victims, setting a record for the Catholic Church in Australia), Father David O'Hearn (serving a 23-year sentence)<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2016-08-22/hunter-catholic-priest-david-ohearn-sentenced-over-child-sex/7771798|title=Hunter Catholic priest David O'Hearn sentenced to more than five years over child sex offences|author=Brown, Michelle|work=ABC News|location=Australia|date=22 August 2016|access-date=22 May 2018}}</ref> and Father James Fletcher (died in jail in 2006).<ref>{{cite news|title=Cases against clergy in Maitland-Newcastle Diocese |work=ABC News |location=Australia |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/infographics/clergy-questioned/ |date=16 May 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100521235945/http://www.abc.net.au/news/infographics/clergy-questioned/ |archivedate=21 May 2010 }}</ref>\n\nJohn Sidney Denham pleaded guilty to 29 child sex charges involving 27 boys under his care while a priest in Newcastle in the 1970s.<ref>{{cite news |title=Priest sex abuse sentence delayed |work=ABC News |location=Australia |date=5 February 2010 |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2010/02/05/2811371.htm |accessdate=5 February 2010 }}</ref> It was alleged that the Archbishop of Adelaide, [[Philip Wilson (bishop)|Philip Wilson]], knew about clerical sexual abuse when serving in the New South Wales' diocese of Maitland-Newcastle in the late 1970s and 1980s.<ref name=Crittenden /> On 27 July 2012, John Pirona was found dead in his car five days after leaving a letter ending \"too much pain\", this referring to his abuse by a paedophile priest in 1979 when Pirona was 12, the event occurring a year after Maitland-Newcastle bishop Leo Clarke was informed that the priest was a sex offender.<ref>{{cite news|author=McCarthy, Joanne|title=Abused Man Takes His Life|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|date=28 July 2012|page=3}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 July 2012, NSW Police in Strike Force Lantle announced they would be providing prosecutors with evidence that Father Brian Lucas, general secretary of the Australian Catholic Bishops Conference, Archbishop Wilson of Adelaide and Michael Malone, retired Bishop of Maitland-Newcastle, had committed the offence of concealing a serious crime under s316 of the ''[[Crimes Act 1900]]'' (NSW) in concealing child sexual abuse by the priest Denis McAlinden (now deceased) in the Maitland-Newcastle diocese. The evidence includes an admission by then Maitland-Newcastle bishop, Leo Clarke, to McAlinden that \"your good name will be protected by the confidential nature of the process\" despite \"your admission to Father Brian Lucas and other evidence\" and a letter from the late Maitland-Newcastle monsignor Patrick Cotter to Bishop Clarke that McAlinden \"feels no such inclination towards mature females but towards the little ones. I have never heard of this condition before and knowing Father McAlinden as we do, we do not think it can be real serious.\"<ref>{{cite news|author1=McCarthy, Joanne|author2=Besser, Linton|title=Police Move on Priests Over Abuse 'Cover-Up'|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|date=31 July 2012|page=1 |url=https://www.smh.com.au/nsw/police-move-on-priests-over-abuse-coverup-20120730-23aba.html|accessdate=31 July 2012}}</ref> In November 2012 the [[Premier of New South Wales]], [[Barry O'Farrell]], ordered a special commission of inquiry into allegations of sexual abuse by Catholic clergy in this diocese and whether the church had hindered police investigations.<ref>{{cite news|authorlink=Imre Salusinszky|author=Salusinszky, Imre|title=Farrell orders inquiry into Catholic church sex abuse investigations|work=[[The Australian]]|date=9 November 2012|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/nation/ofarrell-orders-inquiry-into-catholic-church-sex-abuse-investigations/story-e6frg6nf-1226513826422 |accessdate=12 November 2012 }}</ref> Presided over by [[Margaret Cunneen]] {{post-nominals|country=AUS|SC}}, she reported her findings to the [[Governor of New South Wales]], [[Marie Bashir]], on 30 May 2014.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-05-30/hunter-child-abuse-special-commission-of-inquiry-clears-police/5488942|title=Special Commission of Inquiry clears police, finds whistleblower Peter Fox 'not credible' over child abuse cover-up claims|last1=Ansari|first1=Tahmina|work=[[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]] |location=Australia |date=30 May 2014|accessdate=17 April 2015}}</ref> On 22 May 2018, the Newcastle Local Court found Wilson guilty of the charge of failing to report allegations of child sexual abuse by Fletcher in 1976.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-05-22/adelaide-archbishop-found-guilty-of-concealing-child-abuse/9783612 |title=Archbishop of Adelaide Philip Wilson found guilty of covering up child sexual abuse |first=Nancy |last=Notzon |newspaper=ABC News |accessdate=22 May 2018 |date=22 May 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"verdict\">{{cite news|title=Catholic Archbishop found guilty of covering up child sexual abuse|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-05-22/adelaide-archbishop-found-guilty-of-concealing-child-abuse/9783612|accessdate=22 May 2018|work=ABC News|date=22 May 2018|language=en-AU}}</ref>  Wilson was given a maximum sentence of 12 months in detention for concealing child sexual abuse in the 1970s.<ref>{{cite news|title=Archbishop Philip Wilson sentenced for concealing child sex abuse |work=BBC |location=Australia |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-australia-44692396/ |date=3 July 2018 }}</ref>  On 6 December 2018, Wilson was acquitted of all the charges of which he had previously been found guilty. The Director of Public Prosecutions had been reported to be considering a challenge in the Supreme Court of New South Wales but on 20 December, announced that there were no reasonable prospects of success of appeal on errors of law.\n\nOn 15 February 2017 it was reported that The Catholic Church in Australia had secretly paid the equivalent of $276.1&nbsp;million in compensation to thousands of people sexually abused as children by priests and religious brothers.<ref name=settlementoz>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2017/feb/16/australian-catholic-church-has-paid-276m-to-abuse-victims-so-far-inquiry-shows|title=Australian Catholic church has paid $276m to abuse victims so far, inquiry shows|agency=[[Australian Associated Press]]|author=|work=[[Guardian Australia]]|date=16 February 2017|access-date=22 May 2018}}</ref> Between 1980 and 2015, the Christian Brothers, which operated a number of residential facilities, made the highest number of payments at 763, totaling $48.5&nbsp;million.<ref name=settlementoz />  Most reported incidents of sex abuse occurred between 1950 and 1989.<ref name=settlementoz />  Some reported incidents occurred as early as the 1920s and the latest after 2010.<ref name=settlementoz />\n\nIn May 2019, Fr. Vincent Gerald Ryan, who had previously served 14 years in jail for sex abusing for abusing 34 boys from 1973 to 1991, was jailed for at least 14 months for sex abuse he committed against two altar boys during this timeframe which weren't prosecuted.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://7news.com.au/news/crime/former-catholic-priest-jailed-for-sexual-abuse-of-two-altar-boys-in-hunter-region-c-126587|title='Burn in hell': Former priest Vincent Ryan to go back behind bars|date=22 May 2019|website=7NEWS.com.au}}</ref>\n\n====Diocese of Wagga Wagga====\n{{see also|Roman Catholic Diocese of Wagga Wagga}}\nIn 2002, Vincent Kieran Kiss, 70, pleaded guilty in the Sydney District Court for sex crimes against four teenage boys, aged 13 to 17, between 1966 and 1973 at locations including [[Albury, New South Wales|Albury]], [[Yass, New South Wales|Yass]] and Sydney. Kiss was the Diocesan Director of Youth in Wagga Wagga at the time of the offences and the four victims were members of the Young Christian Students Association.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2002/08/07/1028157962938.html |title=Father Kiss pleads guilty to sex charges |work=The Age |location=Australia |date=8 August 2002 |accessdate=18 September 2011 }}</ref>\n\n====Diocese of Wollongong====\n{{see also|Roman Catholic Diocese of Wollongong}}\nIn 1993, the ''[[Illawarra Mercury]]'' alleged that Gwynneville parish priest Father Peter Lewis Comensoli and Brother Michael Evans had been involved in the sexual abuse of boys.<ref>{{cite journal |work=PANPA Bulletin |date=September 2005 |pages=56\u201357 |url=http://espace.library.uq.edu.au/eserv/UQ:8806/rk_panpa_0905.pdf |format=PDF |title=Guts-and-glory, murder and more during the Mercury\u2019s 150 years |author=Kirkpatrick, Rod |accessdate=18 September 2011 }}</ref><ref name=\"WonderfulWollongong\">{{cite news |url=http://www.abc.net.au/rn/talks/bbing/stories/s328.htm |series=Background Briefing |title=Wonderful Wollongong |work=ABC Radio National |location=Australia |date=30 August 1998 |author=Robinson, Gareth |format=transcript |access-date=16 May 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090216181309/http://www.abc.net.au/rn/talks/bbing/stories/s328.htm |archive-date=16 February 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Comensoli was jailed and was later named during the [[Royal Commission into the New South Wales Police Service|Wood Royal Commission]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.illawarramercury.com.au/news/local/news/general/underbelly-3-a-tale-of-wollongongs-darkest-hour/1531391.aspx?storypage=0 |title=Underbelly 3: A tale of Wollongong's darkest hour |work=Illawarra Mercury |first=Jodie |last=Minus |date=4 June 2009 |accessdate=18 September 2011 }}</ref> Evans committed suicide.<ref name=\"WonderfulWollongong\" />\n\nIn 1996 Father John Gerard Nestor was charged with the 1991 indecent assault of a 15-year-old altar boy. Nestor was initially convicted by a Local Court magistrate and sentenced to a 16 months gaol term which was overturned on an \"all points\" appeal to the District Court. The case ended suddenly when prosecution witnesses were caught in contradictions, Judge Phelen stating that the supposed victim seemed to have difficulty \"distinguishing fact from imagination\". Nestor went on to work as a priest for a number of years in senior appointments. After engaging in secular employment he was [[Loss of clerical state (Catholic Church)|laicised]] in 2009.<ref name=\"age abbott\">{{cite news|url=http://news.theage.com.au/breaking-news-national/abbott-vouched-for-priest-later-struck-off-20130206-2dxoh.html | location=Melbourne | work=The Age | title=Abbott vouched for priest later struck off |date=6 February 2013 |accessdate=15 May 2015 |author= }}</ref> The former Australian prime minister and leader of the [[Australian Liberal Party]], [[Tony Abbott]], provided a character reference for Nestor's trial describing him as \"an upright and virtuous man whom he had known since 1984 while studying at Sydney's St Patrick's Seminary to become a priest\".<ref name=\"age abbott\" /> The ''[[Illawarra Mercury]]'' reported lawyer Chris Murphy suggesting that the Royal Commission into Institutional Responses to Child Sexual Abuse investigate the case of Nestor.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.illawarramercury.com.au/story/1289070/royal-commission-should-examine-nestor-case/ |title=Royal commission 'should examine Nestor case'  |work=[[Illawarra Mercury]] |date=8 February 2013 |accessdate=15 May 2015 |author=Osborne, Paul |agency=AAP }}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Kelvin Gerald Sharkey, 83, was sentenced in the Wollongong District Court to at least 15 months jail for sexually abusing an altar boy on three occasions between 1969 and 1975 when Sharkey was parish priest of St John Vianney's Church at Fairy Meadow and at St Bernard's Church at Batemans Bay.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2010/04/30/2886983.htm |title=Church to deregister sex abuse ex-priest |work=ABC News |location=Australia |date=30 April 2010 |accessdate=18 September 2011 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Marist Brother and former principal of the Mary Immaculate Catholic Parish Primary School in the Sydney suburb of Eagle Vale, plead guilty to four counts of sexually abusing a minor.<ref name=schooldaysconvict>{{cite web|url=https://cruxnow.com/global-church/2018/02/06/australian-bishop-apologizes-school-abuse-calls-victims-come-forward/ |title=Australian bishop apologizes for school abuse, calls on victims to come forward |publisher=Cruxnow.com |date=2018-02-06 |accessdate=2019-09-22}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, then Bishop [[Peter Ingham (bishop)|Peter Ingham]] issued an apology and acknowledged the history of sex abuse at various Catholic schools in the Diocese of Wollongong.<ref name=schooldaysconvict />\n\nIn March 2019, Father Ron Peters, who was formerly listed as the \"Dean and Adiministrator\" of the Diocese of Wollongong,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/dutch.in.wollongong/posts/524194251115327|title=Dutch in Wollongong|website=www.facebook.com}}</ref><ref>[http://www.lumenchristi.org.au/index.php/RonPeters ]{{dead link|date=September 2019}}</ref> was charged with sex abuse.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.camdenadvertiser.com.au/story/5969884/former-campbelltown-priest-charged-with-indecent-assaults-on-boy/|title=Former Campbelltown priest charged with indecent assaults on boy|first=Cydonee|last=Mardon|date=22 March 2019|website=Camden-Narellan Advertiser}}</ref>\n\n====Diocese of Bathurst====\n{{see also|Roman Catholic Diocese of Bathurst in Australia|St Stanislaus College (Bathurst)}}\nSt Stanislaus College Bathurst in the 1970s and 1980s was referred to by an anonymous former student as a \"pedophile paradise\" due to the abusive activities of priests there.<ref>{{cite news |first=Damien |last=Murphy |work=The Sydney Morning Herald |date=6 September 2008 |title=Old boy calls school a pedophile paradise |url=https://www.smh.com.au/news/national/old-boy-calls-school-a-pedophile-paradise/2008/09/05/1220121526764.html |accessdate=22 September 2011 }}</ref> William Stanley Irwin, 55, for instance, a former Catholic brother, was convicted on 31 March 2011 by a jury in the Sydney District Court on two counts of gross indecency on a male under the age of 18 at [[St Stanislaus College (Bathurst)|St Stanislaus' College]] in Bathurst in the mid-1980s. Having been asked by the boy's parents to counsel him in relation to prior sexual abuse, Irwin kissed the youth and initiated mutual masturbation when the pair stayed at the boarding school overnight during a road trip in 1986. Irwin was later a dormitory master at St Stanislaus' for two years and a chaplain and teacher at [[St Aloysius' College (Sydney)|St Aloysius' College]] at Milsons Point.<ref>{{cite news |last=Courts |first=Louise Hall |title=Catholic brother abused boy he was counselling |work= The Sydney Morning Herald |date=1 April 2011 |url=https://www.smh.com.au/nsw/catholic-brother-abused-boy-he-was-counselling-20110331-1cnhj.html |accessdate=1 April 2011 }}</ref>\n\nKevin Francis Phillips, similarly, pleaded guilty in a Sydney District Court on 3 December 2010 to four counts of gross indecency with a child under the age of 18. Phillips was sentenced on 21 April 2011 to a total of 15 months jail. On the first three counts, he was sentenced to a concurrent term of nine months starting on 21 April 2011 and expiring on 20 January 2012. On the final charge of gross indecency by a male with a male under 18 years, Phillips was sentenced to a term of nine months to start on 21 October 2011 and expiring on 20 July 2012 with a non-parole period of three months.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.smh.com.au/nsw/former-priest-denies-assault-after-channelling-voice-of-dead-20101115-17ufc.html |agency=AAP |title=Sixth teacher charged over sex abuse |work=The Australian |date=5 May 2009 |accessdate=22 November 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"SMHPhillips\">{{cite news |url=https://www.smh.com.au/nsw/stannies-priest-convicted-of-abuse-20101203-18ju2.html |author=Marr, David |authorlink=David Marr (journalist) |title=Stannies priest convicted of abuse |work=The Sydney Morning Herald |date=4 December 2010 |accessdate=4 December 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.centralwesterndaily.com.au/news/local/news/general/exstannies-priest-jailed/2158818.aspx |title=Ex-Stannies priest jailed |work=Central Western Daily |location=Australia |date=11 May 2011 |accessdate=11 May 2011}}</ref>\n\nBrian Joseph Spillane also was convicted on 30 November 2010 on nine counts of indecent assault against three girls aged between eight and seventeen while he was based in Sydney in about 1979, a Vincentian priest at that time. During bail proceedings it was heard that Spillane faced a further 135 charges relating to alleged offences against boys at St Stanislaus' College whilst Spillaine was chaplain. These latter charges were expected to be heard in four more trials that were expected to last until late 2011. Spillaine was refused bail.<ref name=\"SMHGodHelpMe\">{{cite news |url=https://www.smh.com.au/nsw/god-help-me-former-priest-found-guilty-of-child-abuse-20101130-18fe9.html |last=Marr |first=David |title=God help me: former priest found guilty of child abuse |work=The Sydney Morning Herald |date=1 December 2010 |accessdate=4 December 2010 }}</ref> After a court-ordered media blackout was lifted, in place since 2013, it was reported in 2016 that Spillane was convicted of assaults on five St Stanislaus' College students after a trial in 2013, and in 2015 he pleaded guilty to assaults on four boys at the school in the late 1980s. It was reported that during 2016 Spillane was convicted of attacks on five students between 1974 and 1990.<ref name=\"SMH2016\">{{cite news |url=https://www.smh.com.au/nsw/notorious-paedophile-brian-spillane-convicted-of-more-stannies-sex-assaults-20161205-gt4hh1.html |author=Gardiner, Stephanie |title=Notorious paedophile Brian Spillane convicted of more Stannies sex assaults |work=The Sydney Morning Herald |date=5 December 2016 |accessdate=10 December 2016 }}</ref> Spillane, who is currently in custody, was sentenced in February 2017 to an additional nine years in prison, and is not eligible for parole.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-02-16/paedophile-priest-jailed-for-nine-years/8275458|title=Paedophile priest Brian Spillane jailed for nine years|first=Sean|last=Rubinsztein-Dunlop|date=16 February 2017|website=ABC News}}</ref>\n\n==== Diocese of Parramatta ====\nIn 1992, after allegations arose that a priest had been sexually abusing some of his parishioners, a meeting was held between the accused priest and three senior members of clergy. As a result of the meeting the priest was banned from conducting Mass, but was otherwise permitted to continue serving as a priest. The priest was laicised in 2005. In 2012, allegations arose through the ''[[Four Corners (Australian TV program)|Four Corners]]'' television program that the priest admitted to child sexual abuse at the 1992 meeting, and that the senior clergy present chose not to report the allegations to police. Cardinal [[George Pell]] subsequently denied that the priest admitted to sexual abuse at the meeting.<ref>{{cite news |last=Allard |first=Tom |date=4 July 2012 |title=Calls for royal commission over alleged cover-up of Catholic abuse |url=https://www.smh.com.au/opinion/political-news/calls-for-royal-commission-over-alleged-coverup-of-catholic-abuse-20120703-21flg.html |accessdate=6 July 2012 |work=The Sydney Morning Herald}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2010, Fr. Robert MacGregor Fuller began serving a 6-18 month sentence months after pleading guilty to sending both a sexually lurid video broadcast of himself and sexually lurid text messages to a 13-year-old girl in the summer of 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2010-02-24/priest-jailed-but-celibacy-vow-cruel/342040 |title=Priest jailed but celibacy vow &#039;cruel&#039; |publisher=Abc.net.au |date=2010-02-24 |accessdate=2019-09-22}}</ref>\n\n===Archdiocese of Melbourne===\n{{Main|Sexual abuse scandal in Melbourne archdiocese}}\n{{update|section|date=April 2020}}\nThe Chief Commissioner of Victoria Police in a submission to a parliamentary inquiry established in April 2012 stated that Melbourne archdiocese's ''Melbourne Response'' process, under which victims may not be legally represented appeared to \"be a de facto substitute for criminal justice\" that was detrimental to prosecuting suspected sexual criminals.<ref name=\"Jane Lee 2012\">{{cite news |author=Lee, Jane |title=Police Slam Catholic Church. Investigations impeded, accused abusers moved on, inquiry told |work=[[The Age]] |date=11 October 2012 |url= |accessdate= |page= }}</ref> He noted that though the ''Melbourne Response'' states on its website that in the past 14 years the church has compensated 300 people as victims of sexual abuse and identified 86 offenders of whom 60 were priests, not one complainant was referred to Victoria Police.<ref name=\"Jane Lee 2012\"/> The report stated that the process of moving offenders to other positions in the church restricted capacity to bring them to account and promoted a culture of secrecy that hindered more victims speaking out. The ''Melbourne Response's'' system, the report states, has outdated process that include requiring victims to confront alleged offenders.<ref name=\"Jane Lee 2012\"/>\n\nNotable cases have included: [[Michael Charles Glennon]] - sentenced to 22 years jail with a non-parole period of 15 years for 23 offences against children, including rape, indecent assault, gross indecency, sexually penetrating a child under the age of 16 and sexually penetrating a child under the age of 10.;<ref>{{cite news |author=Topsfield, Jewel |date=10 October 2003 |title=Notorious pedophile guilty |work=[[Herald Sun]] |url=http://www.poynter.org/dg.lts/id.46/aid.50861/column.htm |accessdate=11 December 2006 |publisher=The Poynter Institute |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060521203333/http://www.poynter.org/dg.lts/id.46/aid.50861/column.htm# |archive-date=21 May 2006 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> David Daniel - sentenced to six years jail with a non-parole period of four years and six months for molesting four boys, a girl and an adult male;<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.starnewsgroup.com.au/story/46544 |work=Mountain Views Mail |title=Hear the truth |first=Kath |last=Gannaway |date=7 August 2007 |accessdate=18 September 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071028222634/http://www.starnewsgroup.com.au/story/46544 |archivedate=28 October 2007 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and Wilfred James Baker -  sentenced to four years in prison (parole after 2 years) for 16 counts of indecent assault and one of gross indecency, involving eight boys, aged 10 to 13, over a 20-year period between 1960 and 1979.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2002/05/03/1019441435037.html |title=Speak no evil |author=Ellingsen, Peter |date=4 May 2002 |work=The Age |accessdate=30 January 2012 |location=Melbourne}}</ref> Three priests, Michael Aulsebrook, Frank Klep and David Rapson, were investigated and prosecuted for sexual abuse which took place at Rupertswood College Sunbury in the 1990s.<ref>{{cite news |last=Lowe |first= Adrian |date=23 August 2011 |title=Sunbury priest jailed for sex abuse |work=The Age |location=Australia |url=http://www.theage.com.au/victoria/sunbury-priest-jailed-for-sex-abuse-20110822-1j6p5.html |accessdate=17 September 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Stayner |first=Guy |date=25 June 2004 |title=Paedophile priest arrested in Melbourne |work=Lateline |location=Australia |url=http://www.abc.net.au/lateline/content/2004/s1140908.htm |accessdate=17 September 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121113093957/http://www.abc.net.au/lateline/content/2004/s1140908.htm |archive-date=13 November 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Daly |first=Martin |date=24 July 2004 |title=Priest used drink on boys: victim |work=The Age |location=Australia |url=http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2004/07/23/1090464864785.html |accessdate=17 September 2011 }}</ref> Rapson was jailed in 2013 for at least 13 years, with the possibility of parole after 10 years, for molesting 8 students at a Catholic school in Melbourne between 1973 and 1990.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/nation/ex-priest-david-edwin-rapson-jailed-for-heartless-sex-abuse-of-students/news-story/415a0131067d8ecf5d72e3c698008a6a|title=Ex-priest David Edwin Rapson jailed for 'heartless' sex abuse of students|author=Pia Akerman|newspaper=The Australian|date=October 17, 2013|accessdate=February 28, 2019}}</ref> Kelp was jailed for 10 and a half years in 2014 after he pleaded guilty to 15 sex offences involving many boys, including siblings at the school aged between 11 and 15, between the 1970s and 1980s and will be eligible for parole six and a half years into his sentence.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-05-26/former-priest-frank-klep-sentenced-to-10-years-in-prison/5477560|title=Frank Klep, former Victorian Catholic priest and teacher at Salesian College, sentenced to 10 years in prison|author=Peta Crayon|publisher=ABC|date=May 26, 2014|accessdate=February 28, 2019}}</ref> Aulsebrook, who was convicted in a retrial, received a sentence on 7 and a half years in 2018 for raping a 12-year-old boy at the Salesian College boarding school in 1988 and will be eligible for parole four and half years in his sentence.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/victoria/ex-priest-who-drugged-and-raped-12-year-old-boy-gets-reduced-jail-time-20180803-p4zvcf.html|title=Ex-priest who drugged and raped 12-year-old boy gets reduced jail time|author=Amber Wilson|newspaper=The Age|date=August 3, 2018|accessdate=February 28, 2019}}</ref> Former Melbourne Archbishop and former high ranking Roman Curia official Cardinal [[George Pell]] was sent to jail on 27 February 2019, two months after being convicted of molesting two choir boys.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.9news.com.au/national/george-pell-conviction-child-sex-offences-first-night-in-prison-melbourne-cardinal-pell-news/e3c12c46-159a-430c-b7e7-3fa1f91b6396|title=Pell wakes up in \u2018Boneyard\u2019 prison after child sex offences conviction|website=www.9news.com.au}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ncronline.org/news/accountability/cardinal-pell-jailed-australia-ahead-march-13-sentencing|title=Cardinal Pell jailed in Australia ahead of March 13 sentencing|date=27 February 2019|website=National Catholic Reporter}}</ref> Judge Peter Kidd sentenced Pell on 13 March 2019 to serve six years in jail, with three years and eight months non-parole period.<ref>{{cite news |title=George Pell to be sentenced for child sex abuse |url=https://www.9news.com.au/2019/03/13/08/57/george-pell-sentencing-child-sex-abuse-live-coverage-catholic-church-news-melbourne |work=9News |date=13 March 2019 |accessdate=13 March 2019 }}</ref> In August 2019, the [[Victorian Court of Appeal]] rejected an Pell's appeal to have his convictions overturned.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/live/2019/aug/21/cardinal-george-pell-appeal-sexual-assault-conviction |title=Cardinal Pell likely to be stripped of Order of Australia \u2013 as it happened |work=[[Guardian Australia]] |date=21 August 2019 |access-date=22 September 2019 |author=McGown, Michael }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/australasia/cardinal-george-pell-child-sex-abuse-conviction-upheld-australia-catholic-church-vatican-court-a9072406.html |title=Cardinal George Pell has child sex abuse convictions upheld by Australian court |author=Austin, Henry |work=[[The Independent]] |location=United Kingdom |date=21 August 2019 |access-date=22 September 2019 }}</ref> Pell has since sought leave to have the matter heard in the [[High Court of Australia|High Court]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-09-17/george-pell-to-appeal-to-the-high-court/11437796 |title=George Pell seeks leave to appeal child sex abuse convictions in High Court |first=Sarah |last=Farnsworth |work=[[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]] |date=17 September 2019 |access-date=22 September 2019}}</ref> On 7 April 2020, Pell won his appeal with the Australian High Court and soon afterwards released from prison after serving 13 months of his six year prison sentence.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/cardinal-george-pell-be-released-prison-after-australia-s-high-n1178036|title=Cardinal George Pell out of prison after Australia's High Court overturns abuse convictions|author=Phil Helsel and The Associated Press|publisher=NBC News|date=7 April 2020|accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Diocese of Ballarat====\n{{see also|Roman Catholic Diocese of Ballarat}}\nThe [[Royal Commission into Institutional Responses to Child Sexual Abuse#Catholic Church authorities in Ballarat|Royal Commission into Institutional Responses to Child Sexual Abuse]] final report published on 15 December 2017 found that 139 people made a claim of child sexual abuse to the Diocese of Ballarat between 1980 and 2015 and that there was 21 alleged perpetrators identified in claims. Of the 21 alleged and convicted perpetrators 17 were priests which is 8.7% of the priests who ministered during this period.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.childabuseroyalcommission.gov.au/sites/default/files/final_report_-_volume_16_religious_institutions_book_2.pdf|title=Final Report: Volume 16, Religious institutions Book 2|last=Commonwealth of Australia|date=December 2017|website=Royal Commission into Institutional Responses to Child Sexual Abuse|page=106}}</ref>\n\nThe Royal Commissions final report of Catholic Church authorities in Ballarat was released on 6 December.<ref name=\"Gemma.Choy\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.childabuseroyalcommission.gov.au/media-releases/report-catholic-church-authorities-ballarat-released|title=Report into Catholic Church authorities in Ballarat released {{!}} Royal Commission into Institutional Responses to Child Sexual Abuse|last=Gemma.Choy|date=2017-12-06|work=Royal Commission into Institutional Responses to Child Sexual Abuse|access-date=2017-12-16|language=en}}</ref> The Commission found that [[Ronald Mulkearns|Bishop Mulkearns]] failed to take action \"Bishop Mulkearns again was derelict in his duty in failing to take any effective action to have (infamous paedophile Gerald) Ridsdale referred to police and to restrict Ridsdale's contact with children\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thecourier.com.au/story/5103641/we-failed-and-we-are-sorry-church-responds-to-scathing-report/?cs=62|title=We failed and we are sorry: church responds to scathing report|last=Wrigley|first=Brendan|date=2017-12-06|work=The Courier|access-date=2017-12-16|language=en}}</ref> The Commission pointed out to the structure of the Diocese, culture and governance, concluding: \u201cThe most likely explanation for the conduct of Bishop Mulkearns and other senior clergy in the Diocese was that they were trying to minimise the risk of scandal and protect the reputation of the Catholic Church.\" The Melbourne report found that former Ballarat Diocese [[Peter Connors|Bishop Peter Connors]] was part of a culture that practiced \"using oblique or euphemistic language in correspondence and records concerning complaints of child sexual abuse\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thecourier.com.au/story/5102536/royal-commission-slams-former-ballarat-bishop-in-melbourne-report/?cs=62|title=Royal Commission slams former Ballarat Bishop in Melbourne report|last=Wrigley|first=Brendan|date=2017-12-05|work=The Courier|access-date=2017-12-16|language=en}}</ref>\n\nBelow are some extracts from the conclusion of the Royal Commission into Institutional Responses to Child Sexual Abuse's report into Case Study 28 \u2013 Catholic Church authorities in Ballarat:<blockquote>This case study exposed a catastrophic failure in the leadership of the Diocese and ultimately in the structure and culture of the Church over decades to effectively respond to the sexual abuse of children by its priests. That failure led to the suffering and often irreparable harm to children, their families and the wider community. That harm could have been avoided if the Church had acted in the interests of children rather than in its own interests.</blockquote><blockquote>Euphemistic and elliptical language was often used in correspondence and minutes to mask the true nature of the conduct discussed. There was repeated reference to \u2018pressures\u2019, \u2018strains\u2019 and unspecified \u2018problems\u2019. On occasions, records were deliberately not made or kept or were destroyed.</blockquote><blockquote>The result of these inexcusable failures was that more children were sexually abused by Catholic clergy in the Diocese. There was a catastrophic institutional failure which resulted in many children being sexually abused. We heard about the devastating, often lifelong, consequences in the lives of those children. The welfare of children was not the primary concern of Bishop Mulkearns and other senior members of the Diocese when responding to complaints and allegation of child sexual abuse against their priests. There is no doubt it should have been.<ref name=\"Gemma.Choy\"/></blockquote>The report on Ballarat also described the impact it had on victims. One section outlines suicide and premature death caused from the abuse. One victim said<blockquote>Newspapers don\u2019t report suicides, so the public doesn\u2019t hear about the broken families and their shattered lives, about the unseen impact of institutional child sexual abuse. Children are left behind and they don\u2019t understand why. It doesn\u2019t end when the abuse ends.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.childabuseroyalcommission.gov.au/sites/default/files/case_study_28_-_findings_report_-_catholic_church_authorities_in_ballarat_catholic_church_authorities_in_ballarat2.pdf|title=Royal Commission into Institutional Responses to Child Sexual Abuse: Catholic Church authorities in Ballarat - Report of Case Study No. 28|website=Royal Commission into Institutional Responses to Child Sexual Abuse|pages=433\u2013436}}</ref></blockquote>Other harms are outlined. Another victim outlines the general harm in the Ballarat community:<blockquote>Such chronic sexual abuse in the Ballarat community has led to a large number of men who are not able to be productive members of society and in neglect have become either emotional, social or financial burdens upon the community.<ref name=\":0\" /></blockquote>One victim who told their story to the Royal Commission was Paul Levey was sent to live with Ridsdale at the age of 14 at the presbytery in Mortlake.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-3472019/The-disturbing-picture-vile-paedophile-Gerald-Ridsdale-sitting-helpless-14-year-old-victim-Paul-Levey.html|title=The picture of paedophile Gerald Ridsdale with a 14-year-old victim|work=Mail Online|access-date=2017-12-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.standard.net.au/story/5103743/claims-of-sexual-abuse-at-south-west-parishes-fell-on-deaf-ears-commission-finds/|title=Claims of sexual abuse at south-west parishes fell on deaf ears, Commission finds|last=Patterson|first=Andrew Thomson and Monique|date=2017-12-06|work=The Standard|access-date=2017-12-29|language=en}}</ref> The Levey said he was \"sexually abused all the time just about every day\" and the Commission heard evidence that Ronald Mulkearns was among a number of clergy who knew Ridsdale had a boy living with him, but failed to intervene.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/audio/2017/dec/11/the-reckoning-part-1-david-marr-on-the-road-to-the-child-sexual-abuse-commission-podcast|title=The Reckoning part one: the road to the royal commission \u2013 podcast {{!}} David Marr|last=Marr|first=David|date=2017-12-11|work=The Guardian|access-date=2017-12-29|last2=Martignoni|first2=Miles|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|last3=Davey|first3=Melissa}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/abuse-royal-commission-george-pell-must-have-known-says-ridsdale-victim-20160301-gn7g2l.html|title=Abuse royal commission: George Pell must have known, says Ridsdale victim|last=Cunningham|first=Melissa|date=2016-03-02|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=2017-12-29|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/victoria/ballarat-dioceses-catastrophic-failure-led-to-more-abuse-commission-finds-20171206-gzztn4.html|title=Ballarat diocese's 'catastrophic' failure led to more abuse, commission finds|last=Cunningham|first=Melissa|date=2017-12-07|work=The Age|access-date=2017-12-29|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.traumainreligion.com/paul_levey0.php|title=About my life and my abuse by the Catholic paedophile priest Gerald Francis Ridsdale|website=www.traumainreligion.com|access-date=2017-12-29}}</ref> The commission found that Mulkearns \"ignored\" pleas from Paul Levey's mother who was \"concerned about the situation and sought his assistance\" even though \"By this time, Bishop Mulkearns knew of Ridsdale\u2019s admission of offending against boys.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2017/dec/06/catholic-bishop-cared-little-for-children-and-left-them-in-danger-royal-commission-finds|title=Catholic bishop cared little for children and left them in danger, royal commission finds|last=Davey|first=Melissa|date=2017-12-06|work=The Guardian|access-date=2017-12-29|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> The Commission stated that Bishop Mulkearns\u2019 response to Paul Levey living with Ridsdale in the Mortlake presbytery \"demonstrated a total absence of concern for the welfare of that boy\".<ref name=\":02\">{{cite web|url=https://www.childabuseroyalcommission.gov.au/sites/default/files/case_study_28_-_findings_report_-_catholic_church_authorities_in_ballarat_catholic_church_authorities_in_ballarat2.pdf|title=Royal Commission into Institutional Responses to Child Sexual Abuse: Catholic Church authorities in Ballarat - Report of Case Study No. 28|website=Royal Commission into Institutional Responses to Child Sexual Abuse|page=318}}</ref> The Royal Commission into Institutional Responses to Child Sexual Abuse found that the then Bishop of Ballarat Diocese, [[James O'Collins]], had received a complaint in the 1960s that Father Gerald Ridsdale had sexually abused a boy but did not take action.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-08-06/catholic-church-ballarat-diocese-abuse-compensation-claim/8766482|title='No moral compass': Priest's abuse victim slams church over compo dispute|date=2017-08-06|work=ABC News|access-date=2017-12-22|language=en-AU}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.childabuseroyalcommission.gov.au/sites/default/files/final_report_-_volume_16_religious_institutions_book_2.pdf|title=Royal Commission into Institutional Responses to Child Sexual Abuse: Final Report: Volume 16, Religious institutions Book 2|website=Royal Commission into Institutional Responses to Child Sexual Abuse|page=127}}</ref> The royal commission was also told Bishop [[Ronald Mulkearns]] knew in 1975 that Ridsdale had abused boys and again did nothing to stop the abuse from occurring.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.news.com.au/national/courts-law/vile-paedophile-gerald-ridsdale-will-give-evidence-at-royal-commission-today/news-story/63054c92d762e9c3d53629b8da59ccab|title=Paedo Ridsdale: \u2018I went haywire with altar boys\u2019|work=NewsComAu|access-date=2017-12-22}}</ref>\n\nA priest, [[Gerald Ridsdale]], was jailed in 1994 for 18 years, with a minimum of 15 years, after pleading guilty to 46 counts of child sexual offences, including buggery, indecent assault and gross indecency, committed over two decades on 21 victims.<ref name=\"the-age-good-men-of-the-cloth\">{{cite news | last = Ellingsen | first = Peter | title = Ballarat's good men of the cloth | work = [[The Age]] | date = 14 June 2002 | url = http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2002/06/13/1023864324376.html | accessdate = 19 June 2010 | location=Melbourne}}</ref> In 2006, he pleaded guilty to 35 additional charges relating to [[indecent assault]] against 10 boys.<ref name=\"abc-guilty-plea\">{{cite news |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2006/08/07/1708350.htm |title=Former priest pleads guilty to child abuse |work=[[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]] |date=7 August 2006 |accessdate=25 November 2009 }}</ref> On these charges, he was sentenced to 13 years imprisonment, with a minimum of seven years.<ref name=\"the-age-criticism\">{{cite news | url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/national/victims-slam-pedophile-sentence/2006/08/11/1154803068610.html |accessdate=25 November 2009 |location=Melbourne |work=The Age |first=Jamie |last=Berry |title=Victims slam pedophile sentence |date=11 August 2006}}</ref> A few of his victims criticised the sentence.<ref name=\"the-age-criticism\" /> Ridsdale would have been eligible for parole in August 2013, at the age of 79.<ref name=\"the-age-criticism\" /> On 20 June 2013, Ridsdale was again charged by Victoria Police with an additional 84 offences against 14 victims committed between 1961 and 1981.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2013-05-31/paedophile-priest-gerald-ridsdale-interviewed-by-detectives/4724678 |title=Paedophile priest Gerald Ridsdale interviewed over new abuse claims |work=[[AM (Australian radio series)|AM]], [[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]] |location=Australia |date=31 May 2014 |access-date=22 May 2015 |author=Donovan, Samantha }}</ref> He pleaded guilty to 29 counts (27 of indecent assault, one count of buggery and one count of carnal knowledge of a girl under the age of 16) committed between 1960 and 1980 and asked for a further 27 counts to be taken into consideration at sentencing, which will take place at a date to be fixed.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2013-11-18/paedophile-priest-gerald-ridsdale-pleads-guilty-to-new-child-se/5099280 |title=Paedophile priest Gerald Ridsdale pleads guilty to 29 child sex offences |work=[[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]] |location=Australia |date=18 November 2013 |access-date= |author= }}</ref> After pleading guilty to the above charges, including raping and abusing children as young as four, Ridsdale was sentenced to eight years in prison in April 2014 and will be eligible for parole in April 2019.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-04-08/paedophile-priest-gerald-ridsdale-sentenced/5375506 |title=Paedophile priest Gerald Ridsdale sentenced to 8 years in jail for child abuse |date=18 March 2014 |work=[[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]] |location=Australia |access-date=21 May 2015 }}</ref> The latest charges bring the tally of Ridsdale's confirmed victims to 54.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-03-18/victim-of-paedophile-priest-felt-dirty2c-scared-and-confused2/5328526 |title=Victims of paedophile priest Gerald Ridsdale felt dirty, scared and confused, court told |work=[[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]] |location=Australia |date=18 March 2014 |access-date=21 May 2015 |author= }}</ref> In May 2015 Ridsdale gave an account of his offending in evidence to the Royal Commission on Institutional Responses to Child Sexual Abuse.<ref>J. Franklin, [http://www.maths.unsw.edu.au/~jim/franklinridsdale.pdf Gerald Ridsdale, pedophile priest, in his own words], ''Journal of the Australian Catholic Historical Society'' 36 (2105), 219-230.</ref>\n\nRidsdale pleaded guilty to a further 20 offences against 10 boys and a girl on 13 April 2017. These offences were committed between 1961 and 1988 in western Victoria and are expected to extend his release date further into the future.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-04-13/paedophile-priest-gerald-ridsdale-pleads-guilty/8442132 |title=Gerald Ridsdale, paedophile priest, pleads guilty to more sexual abuse involving 11 children in western Victoria |first=Emma |last=Younger |publisher=[[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]] |date=13 April 2017 |accessdate=13 April 2017}}</ref>  On 15 August 2017 Ridsdale pleaded guilty to 23 charges including two counts of rape and one of buggery, for abusing 12 children, 11 boys and  aged 6 to 13, between 1962 and 1988 in the Victoria state city of Ballarat and the surrounding area.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/australia-court-hears-harrowing-accounts-child-abuse-diocese-linked-vatican-651096|title=Australian court hears harrowing accounts of child abuse by pedophile priest|first=Sofia Lotto Persio On 8/15/17 at 1:54 PM|last=EDT|date=15 August 2017|website=Newsweek}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2017/aug/15/paedophile-priest-gerald-ridsdale-abused-girl-on-church-altar-victorian-court-told|title=Paedophile priest Gerald Ridsdale abused girl on church altar, Victorian court told|first=Australian Associated|last=Press|date=15 August 2017|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 August 2011, [[Congregation of Christian Brothers#Australia|Robert Charles Best]], a [[Congregation of Christian Brothers|Christian Brother]], was sentenced in the Victorian County Court to 14 years and nine months jail, with a non-parole period of 11 years and three months, for 27 offences involving sexual abuse of 11 boys. Best taught at Catholic primary and secondary schools in Ballarat, Box Hill and Geelong (all in Victoria, Australia) between the 1960s and 1980s. Best has been convicted by a jury and has pleaded guilty to more than 40 child sex offences against dozens of students, some as young as eight years old.<ref name=Best>{{cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2011-07-25/christian-brother-found-guilty-of-chiild-sex-offences/2809210 |title=Christian brother found guilty of child sex offences |work=[[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]] |location=Australia |date=25 July 2011 |accessdate=25 July 2011 |author= }}</ref> {{as of|2011}} Best had not been expelled by the Christian Brothers and the order had expended more than {{AUD}}1&nbsp;million on his legal costs.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/breaking-news/pedophile-christian-brother-robert-bests-appeal-an-insult-victims/story-fn3dxity-1226142054531 |title=Pedophile Christian Brother Robert Best's appeal an insult-victims |work=The Australian |date=20 September 2011 |accessdate=31 October 2011 |author=Cresswell, Joel |agency=AAP }}</ref> In May 2013, the Christian Brothers admitted to Victoria's parliamentary inquiry into child abuse they did what they could to defend members accused of sexual assault against children. They admitted to hiring a private investigator to follow one of Best's victims. In addition to paying the aforementioned legal costs, the church also paid hundreds of thousands to defend other members also accused of rape.<ref>{{cite news |author=Morris, Madeleine |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2013-05-03/christian-brothers-spent-1m-defending-paedophile/4668944?section=vic |title=Christian Brothers spent $1m defending paedophile |work=[[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]] |location=Australia |date=3 May 2013 |accessdate=3 May 2013 }}</ref>\n\nOn 21 August 2019, Ballarat Bishop [[Paul Bird (bishop)|Paul Bird]] acknowledged that Pell, who had lost his appeal in the state of Victoria, had ties to this Melbourne suffragan diocese and apologized for the history of sex abuse in the Diocese as well.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.standard.net.au/story/6340694/archbishop-urges-pell-verdict-respect/|title=Archbishop urges Pell verdict respect|first=Kaitlyn Offer and Megan|last=Neil|date=21 August 2019|website=The Standard}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 September 2019, the Diocese of Ballarat released a statement admitting that the high-ranking clergy in the Diocese knew of sex abuse claims against Gerald Ridsdale and afterwards made efforts to shield Ridsdale from prosecution.<ref name=ridsdaleprotection>{{cite web|author=Michael Sainsbury |url=https://cruxnow.com/church-in-oceania/2019/09/13/new-admission-by-diocese-could-cost-australian-church-millions-in-claims/ |title=New admission by diocese could cost Australian Church millions in claims |publisher=Cruxnow.com |date=2019-09-13 |accessdate=2019-09-22}}</ref> This confession came in the wake of civil lawsuit filed against the Diocese by one of Ridsdale's victims.<ref name=ridsdaleprotection />\n\nIn addition to the Archdiocese of Melbourne sex abuse charges, Pell also faces numerous sex abuse charges stemming from his time in the Diocese of Ballarat.<ref name=Pellcharged>{{Cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-06-29/cardinal-george-pell-charged-sexual-assault-offences/8547668|title=George Pell told to face court on historical sexual assault charges|date=2017-06-29|work=ABC News|access-date=2020-04-02|language=en-AU}}</ref> The 3 episode miniseries Revelation, which aired on ABC TV on March 17, March 31 and April 2, 2020,<ref>https://www.abc.net.au/radio/programs/abc-news-specials/episode-3/12114314</ref> revealed two men, identified as Bernie and Peter Clarke, who accused Pell of sexually abusing them as boys when he served at the Catholic-run orphanage where they resided in the 1970s.<ref>https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-04-02/george-pell-ballarat-allegations-revelation/12109952</ref> The new sex abuse allegations against Pell were also investigated by Australian journalist [[Sarah Ferguson (journalist)|Sarah Ferguson]].<ref name=pellorphanage>https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-04-02/george-pell-ballarat-allegations-revelation/12109952</ref> Despite the fact that his sex abuse convictions related to his time in the Archdiocese of Melbourne were later overturned, Pell still faces 10 civil lawsuits, with some stemming from his time in the Diocese of Ballarat<ref>https://cruxnow.com/vatican/2020/04/vatican-welcomes-pell-verdict-affirms-anti-abuse-resolve-as-survivors-protest/</ref><ref>https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2019/mar/04/george-pell-to-be-sued-over-alleged-1970s-sexual-abuse-in-ballarat</ref>\n\n===Marist Brothers===\nIn September 2018, Marist Brother Gerard McNamara, 80, was sentenced to nine months in prison for molested five boys who were aspiring athletes at St Paul's Catholic College, where served as principal, in Traralgon between 1970 and 1975.<ref name=maristbrotherconviction /> He also molested one of these boy 30 times.<ref name=maristbrotherconviction>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2018/sep/03/marist-brother-who-sexually-assaulted-five-boys-sentenced-to-nine-months-jail|title=Marist brother who sexually assaulted five boys sentenced to nine months' jail|first=Australian Associated|last=Press|date=3 September 2018|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref> In June 2019, the [[Marist Brothers]] produced a list of 154 members who were accused of sexually abusing children in Australia between 1980 and 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-au/news/australia/the-marist-brothers-and-a-secret-list-of-154-accused-child-sex-offenders/ar-AADmvjB|title=The Marist Brothers and a secret list of 154 accused child sex offenders|website=www.msn.com}}</ref>\n\n===Archdiocese of Brisbane===\nIn June 2010, Brisbane priest Michael Ambrose Endicott plead guilty to take indecent photos of two schoolboys between 1977 and 1978 and received a one-year suspended prison sentence.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://brokenrites.org.au/archives/nletter/page233-michael-ambrose-endicott.html|title=Full story: Father Michael Ambrose Endicott sentenced|website=brokenrites.org.au}}</ref> In March 2019, he received an 18-month prison sentence after being convicted of making boys strip nude for photos during the 1970s and 1980s,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.blayneychronicle.com.au/story/5943329/qld-priest-guilty-of-historical-sex-abuse/|title=Qld priest guilty of historical sex abuse|date=8 March 2019|website=Blayney Chronicle}}</ref> only to have this conviction overturned the next month.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-04-17/catholic-priest-acquitted-of-indecent-dealing-child-charges/11024008|title=Former priest's indecent dealing conviction overturned on appeal|date=17 April 2019|website=ABC News}}</ref>\n\n====Diocese of Townsville====\n{{see also|Roman Catholic Diocese of Townsville}}\nNotable cases include: Neville Joseph Creen - molested young girls while he served as a priest at Mount Isa, north-west Queensland, from 1973 to 1981. In Brisbane District Court on 12 September 2003, Creen (aged 63) was sentenced to three-and-half years' jail with a 14-month minimum after admitting to 34 indecent dealing charges involving 18 girls under the age of 13. One girl was aged just 5 when Creen abused her at a youth camp and later at the home of her grandparents. Creen pleaded guilty to a further six charges on 4 November 2004 and was sentenced to an additional two years jail.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://cathnews.acu.edu.au/309/83.php |work=CathNews |title=Prison for Townsville Diocese priest who molested 18 girls |date=15 September 2003 |accessdate=18 September 2011 }}</ref>\n\n===Archdiocese of Perth===\n{{see also|Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Perth}}\nIn 1995, Gerard William Dick, a self-confessed sexually abusive priest, was sentenced to three and a half years jail for 10 incidents of indecently dealing with boys aged between 8 and 10 at a [[Congregation of Christian Brothers|Christian Brothers]]' orphanage in [[Western Australia]].<ref>{{cite book |first=Bruce |last=Blyth |title=In the Shadow of the Cross: the story of VOICES : how the Christian Brothers' victims fought for justice |publisher=P&B Press |location=Perth, Western Australia |year=1997 |page=106 |isbn=0-646-33774-2 |type=paperback}}</ref>\n\nDavid Christian was fined {{AUD}}10,500 on seven charges of indecently assaulting boys at the Marist Brothers school.<ref>{{cite book |last=Blyth |title=In the Shadow of the Cross: the story of VOICES : how the Christian Brothers' victims fought for justice |page=181 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1994, the [[Parliament of Western Australia]] was presented a petition with 30,000 signatures which demanded an inquiry into the sexual and physical assault that took place in various institutions run by the [[Congregation of Christian Brothers|Christian Brothers]] including [[Castledare Boys' Home]], [[Bindoon, Western Australia|Bindoon]], [[Clontarf Aboriginal College|Clontarf]] and [[Tardun, Western Australia|Tardun]].<ref name=\"lateline sins\">{{cite interview |subject=McDonald, Alex |subject2=Wilkins, John |subject3=Ransom, David |display-authors=etal |interviewer=[[Maxine McKew]] |title=Sins Of The Brothers |type=Interview |url=http://www.abc.net.au/lateline/stories/s17579.htm |format=transcript |work=[[Lateline]] |publisher=[[ABC (Australian TV channel)|ABC TV]] |location=Australia |date=24 November 1998 |access-date=15 May 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080420190410/http://www.abc.net.au/lateline/stories/s17579.htm |archive-date=20 April 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"murray speech\"/>\n\nThe Christian Brothers accepted that there was strong evidence that many of the allegations were true, and made a public apology.<ref name=\"lateline sins\" /> A legal action brought by over 200 former students ran from 1993 in the [[New South Wales Supreme Court]] and was finalised in 1996 with an out of court settlement.<ref name=\"murray speech\">{{cite speech |title=Key note address |author=Murray, Andrew |author-link=Andrew Murray (Australian politician) |date=28 October 2002 |event=1st International Congress on Child Migration |publisher=[[Australian Democrats]] |url=http://www.andrewmurray.org.au/Media/Speech_Display.htm?speech_id=1035&display=1 |access-date=15 May 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090912024052/http://andrewmurray.org.au/Media/Speech_Display.htm?speech_id=1035&display=1 |archivedate=12 September 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, retired Subiaco and Shenton Park priest Patrick Holmes was sentenced to three years jail. He had pled guilty to six child-sex charges dating between 1969 and 1981. He later appeared in court in 2018 and again in 2019, entering a not-guilty plea in response to 16 new charges filed after an investigation by the WA Police's Child Abuse Squad.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brokenrites.org.au/drupal/node/301 |access-date=31 March 2020 |title= This priest has been in jail, and now he faces new charges}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2019, retired Perth priest Allan John Mithen received a 13-month suspended prison sentence after pleading guilty to two counts of sexually abusing an Aborigine girl at a mission in 1965.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sbs.com.au/nitv/nitv-news/article/2019/01/16/its-disgusting-community-anger-former-priest-receives-suspended-sentence|title=\u2018It\u2019s disgusting\u2019: Community anger as former priest receives suspended sentence|website=NITV}}</ref> In March 2019, Joseph Tran, a well known and popular Perth priest, committed suicide after accusations surfaced that he had molested a girl for years.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thenewdaily.com.au/news/state/wa/2019/03/23/wa-priest-accused-of-molesting-teen-girl-found-dead/|title=WA priest accused of molesting teen girl found dead &#124; The New Daily WA priest accused of molesting teen girl found dead|date=23 March 2019|website=The New Daily}}</ref>\n\n====Diocese of Bunbury====\n{{see also|Roman Catholic Diocese of Bunbury}}\nAdrian Richard Van Klooster - pleaded guilty to four counts of indecently dealing with children under the age of 13 and was found with child pornography on his computer.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.catholicweekly.com.au/03/feb/2/15.html |title=Bishop's plea after priest convicted |date=2 February 2003 |accessdate=18 September 2011 |work=The Catholic Weekly |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927065636/http://www.catholicweekly.com.au/03/feb/2/15.html# |archive-date=27 September 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Archdiocese of Hobart===\n\n====Marist Fathers of Tasmania====\n{{see also|Marist Regional College}}\nNotable cases include: in 2007 Gregory Ferguson was sentenced to two years jail (eligible for parole after 12 months) for offences in 1971 against two boys aged 13 at Marist College, Burnie, Tasmania. On 13 December 2007 he was sentenced to an additional three years jail for offences against a third boy.;<ref>{{cite news|title=Pedophile may get parole after one year's prison |url=http://cathnews.acu.edu.au/705/101.php|accessdate=19 January 2011|newspaper=CathNews|date=17 May 2007}}</ref> in 2008 a jury found former priest Roger Michael Bellemore guilty on three counts of maintaining a sexual relationship with a young person under the age of 17 years in the 1960s and 1970s while he was at the same college.<ref>{{cite news |title=Guilty verdict for former priest |work=ABC News |location=Australia |date=12 February 2008 |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2008-02-12/guilty-verdict-for-former-priest/1040112 |accessdate=22 September 2011}}</ref> By December 2018, six former priests who taught at the College had been convicted of committing acts of sexual abuse.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2018/dec/20/former-priest-becomes-sixth-teacher-at-burnie-marist-college-convicted-of-historic-child-sex-offences|title=Former priest becomes sixth teacher at Burnie Marist College convicted of historic child sex offences|first=Calla|last=Wahlquist|date=21 December 2018|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref>\n\n===Archdiocese of Canberra and Goulburn===\n{{Main|Sexual abuse scandal in Canberra and Goulburn archdiocese}}\nIn February 2008, a teacher at Marist College Canberra, Brother John William Chute (also known as Brother Kostka) pleaded guilty in the ACT Magistrates Court to 11 charges of indecently assaulting students of the college during the 1980s.<ref>{{cite news |title=Marist Brother pleads guilty to assaulting boys |work=ABC News |location=Australia |date=21 February 2008 |accessdate=18 September 2011 |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2008/02/21/2168728.htm?section=justin }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.canberratimes.com.au/news/local/news/general/two-years-in-jail-for-brother-kostka/795061.aspx |title=Two years in jail for Brother Kostka |work=The Canberra Times |date=23 June 2008 |accessdate=18 September 2011 |first=Victor |last=Violante }}{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Damages for sexual abuse have also been sought by former students at [[Marist College Canberra]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2008/02/25/2171625.htm |title=More teachers linked to Marist sex abuse case |work=ABC News |location=Australia |date=25 February 2008 |accessdate=18 September 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cathnews.com/article.aspx?aeid=7794 |title=Marists apologise for Canberra abuse |date=24 June 2008 |accessdate=18 September 2011 |work=CathNews |location=Australia |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927121400/http://www.cathnews.com/article.aspx?aeid=7794 |archivedate=27 September 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.canberratimes.com.au/news/local/news/general/schools-paedophile-ring/1565239.aspx |title=School's 'paedophile ring' |work=The Canberra Times |date=11 July 2009 |accessdate=18 September 2011 |first=Victor |last=Violante |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927233708/http://www.canberratimes.com.au/news/local/news/general/schools-paedophile-ring/1565239.aspx# |archive-date=27 September 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> A teacher at [[Daramalan College]] in Canberra was also charged with numerous sexual assaults in 2000; however he committed suicide shortly after he was charged.<ref>{{cite news |work=ABC Canberra |title=Colleges settle sex abuse cases |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2009/12/01/2758197.htm?site=canberra |date=1 December 2009 |accessdate=1 January 2009}}</ref> Seven further charges against Chute relating to alleged offences committed before 1985 were dropped, due to a legal limitation that charges relating to sexual indecency had to be made within a year. In June 2008, Chute was sentenced in the [[Supreme Court of the Australian Capital Territory|ACT Supreme Court]] to six years in jail, serving two years in prison, one year in weekend detention, and three years suspended.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-03-28/canberra-brother-kostka-marist-sex-offences-court/10948376|title=Court accepts notorious paedophile abused boys, but can't convict him|first=Elizabeth|last=Byrne|date=28 March 2019|website=ABC News}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Two years in jail for Brother Kostka |work=The Canberra Times |date=23 June 2008 |url=http://www.canberratimes.com.au/news/local/news/general/two-years-in-jail-for-brother-kostka/795061.aspx |author=Violante, Victor |accessdate=6 September 2019 }}{{dead link|date=May 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Pope Benedict's statement==\n{{Main|Ecclesiastical response to Catholic sex abuse cases}}\nOn 19 July 2008, before a [[wikt:congregation|congregation]] of 3,400 assembled in Sydney's [[St Mary's Cathedral, Sydney|St Mary's Cathedral]], [[Pope Benedict XVI]] lamented that [[child sex abuse]] had taken place and the pain it caused. He also condemned those responsible for it and demanded punishment for them.  However, he did not state or imply that the institutional church, or any of its leaders, accepted any responsibility for what had taken place. His statement reads:<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-pope-australia-abuse-text-idUSL1868657420080719|title=Text of Pope's apology for sexual abuse in Australia|date=2008-07-19|work=Reuters|access-date=2019-11-29|language=en}}</ref>\n<blockquote>\n\"Here I would like to pause to acknowledge the shame which we have all felt as a result of the sexual abuse of minors by some clergy and religious in this country. I am deeply sorry for the pain and suffering the victims have endured and I assure them that, as their pastor, I too share in their suffering. ... Victims should receive compassion and care, and those responsible for these evils must be brought to justice. These misdeeds, which constitute so grave a betrayal of trust, deserve unequivocal condemnation. I ask all of you to support and assist your bishops, and to work together with them in combating this evil. It is an urgent priority to promote a safer and more wholesome environment, especially for young people.\"\n</blockquote>\n\nOn 21 July 2008, before flying out of Australia, Pope Benedict met at St Mary's Cathedral, Sydney, with two male and two female victims of sex abuse by priests. He listened to their stories and celebrated Mass with them.<ref>{{cite news |work=[[The Australian]] |year=2008 |accessdate=21 July 2008 |url=http://www.theaustralian.news.com.au/story/0,25197,24049778-601,00.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080727154145/http://www.theaustralian.news.com.au/story/0%2C25197%2C24049778-601%2C00.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=27 July 2008 |title=Pope Benedict meets abuse victims before flying out |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The [[Premier of New South Wales]], [[Morris Iemma]], said that \"Hopefully it will be a sign of righting the wrongs of the past and of a better future and better treatment by the church of the victims and their families.\"<ref Name=inquirer>{{cite news |url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/breakingnews/world/view/20080719-149455/Popes-Australia-sex-abuse-apology-not-enough----critics |work=Inquirer.net |title=Pope's Australia sex abuse apology not enough -- critics |date=19 July 2008 |location=Philippines |agency=[[Agence France-Presse]] |accessdate=18 September 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120729220022/http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/breakingnews/world/view/20080719-149455/Popes-Australia-sex-abuse-apology-not-enough----critics# |archive-date=29 July 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2008/jul/20/catholicism.australia |location=United Kingdom | work=The Observer | first=Barbara | last=McMahon | title=Pope says he is 'deeply sorry' to Australian sexual abuse victims | date=20 July 2008 |accessdate=18 September 2011}}</ref>\n\nMark Fabbro, a victim of abuse and member of the Catholic Abuse Survivors Collective, said that while he was \"happy to receive the apology, we still consider it indirect and insufficient\".{{Citation needed|date=November 2019}} Chris MacIsaac of the victims' rights advocacy group [[Broken Rites]] said the Pope had taken his apology further than his previous comments on the issue as he has \"never put it quite so strongly before\", but expressed disappointment that the Pope had not made his apology directly to sexual abuse victims.{{Citation needed|date=November 2019}} One Australian victim of sexual abuse by a Catholic priest has stated in the media: \"Dealing with the church itself was a hell of a lot more traumatic than dealing with the abuse''.\"''<ref>{{cite news |first1=Nick |last1=McKenzie |first2=Rafael |last2=Epstein |title=Priests kept working despite investigations |work=Sydney Morning Herald |date=17 May 2010 |url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/priests-kept-working-despite-investigations-20100516-v6f5.html |accessdate=16 May 2010 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Royal Commission into Institutional Responses to Child Sexual Abuse]]\n* [[Roman Catholicism in Australia]]\n* [[William Kamm]] - leader of a schismatic group whose sexual offences predate his schism from the church\n* [[Broken Rites|Broken Rites Australia]] - support and advocacy group for church-related sex abuse victims in Australia\n* [[Catholic sexual abuse cases in New Zealand]]\n* [[Roman Catholic sex abuse cases by country]]\n\n'''General:'''\n*[[Abuse]]\n*[[Child abuse]]\n*[[Child sexual abuse]]\n*[[Religious abuse]]\n*[[Sexual abuse]]\n*[[Sexual misconduct]]\n*[[Spiritual abuse]]\n\n==External links==\n* [https://australiancatholichistoricalsociety.com.au/history-resources/the-sexual-abuse-crisis/ Australian Catholic Historical Society: The Sexual Abuse Crisis]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{SACC}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2011}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Australia}}\n[[Category:Catholic Church sexual abuse scandals in Australia| ]]\n[[Category:Child abuse in Australia]]\n[[Category:Rape in Australia]]\n", "name_user": "HuPi", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eArchdiocese of Sydney:Cardinal Pell case", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Catholic_Church_sexual_abuse_cases_in_Australia"}
